2456 static const char *state_names[] = {
2457 #define LOCKDEP_STATE(__STATE) \
2458         __stringify(__STATE),
2459 #include "lockdep_states.h"
2460 #undef LOCKDEP_STATE
2461 };
2462 
2463 static const char *state_rnames[] = {
2464 #define LOCKDEP_STATE(__STATE) \
2465         __stringify(__STATE)"-READ",
2466 #include "lockdep_states.h"
2467 #undef LOCKDEP_STATE
2468 };
2469 
2470 static inline const char *state_name(enum lock_usage_bit bit)
     /*   */
2471 {
2472         if (bit & LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK)
2473                 return state_rnames[bit >> LOCK_USAGE_DIR_MASK];
2474         else
2475                 return state_names[bit >> LOCK_USAGE_DIR_MASK];
2476 }
2477 
2478 /*
2479  * The bit number is encoded like:
2480  *
2481  *  bit0: 0 exclusive, 1 read lock
2482  *  bit1: 0 used in irq, 1 irq enabled
2483  *  bit2-n: state
2484  */
2485 static int exclusive_bit(int new_bit)
     /*   */
2486 {
2487         int state = new_bit & LOCK_USAGE_STATE_MASK;
2488         int dir = new_bit & LOCK_USAGE_DIR_MASK;
2489 
2490         /*
2491          * keep state, bit flip the direction and strip read.
2492          */
2493         return state | (dir ^ LOCK_USAGE_DIR_MASK);
2494 }
2495 
2496 /*
2497  * Observe that when given a bitmask where each bitnr is encoded as above, a
2498  * right shift of the mask transforms the individual bitnrs as -1 and
2499  * conversely, a left shift transforms into +1 for the individual bitnrs.
2500  *
2501  * So for all bits whose number have LOCK_ENABLED_* set (bitnr1 == 1), we can
2502  * create the mask with those bit numbers using LOCK_USED_IN_* (bitnr1 == 0)
2503  * instead by subtracting the bit number by 2, or shifting the mask right by 2.
2504  *
2505  * Similarly, bitnr1 == 0 becomes bitnr1 == 1 by adding 2, or shifting left 2.
2506  *
2507  * So split the mask (note that LOCKF_ENABLED_IRQ_ALL|LOCKF_USED_IN_IRQ_ALL is
2508  * all bits set) and recompose with bitnr1 flipped.
2509  */
2510 static unsigned long invert_dir_mask(unsigned long mask)
     /*   */
2511 {
2512         unsigned long excl = 0;
2513 
2514         /* Invert dir */
2515         excl |= (mask & LOCKF_ENABLED_IRQ_ALL) >> LOCK_USAGE_DIR_MASK;
2516         excl |= (mask & LOCKF_USED_IN_IRQ_ALL) << LOCK_USAGE_DIR_MASK;
2517 
2518         return excl;
2519 }
2520 
2521 /*
2522  * Note that a LOCK_ENABLED_IRQ_*_READ usage and a LOCK_USED_IN_IRQ_*_READ
2523  * usage may cause deadlock too, for example:
2524  *
2525  * P1                           P2
2526  * <irq disabled>
2527  * write_lock(l1);              <irq enabled>
2528  *                              read_lock(l2);
2529  * write_lock(l2);
2530  *                              <in irq>
2531  *                              read_lock(l1);
2532  *
2533  * , in above case, l1 will be marked as LOCK_USED_IN_IRQ_HARDIRQ_READ and l2
2534  * will marked as LOCK_ENABLE_IRQ_HARDIRQ_READ, and this is a possible
2535  * deadlock.
2536  *
2537  * In fact, all of the following cases may cause deadlocks:
2538  *
2539  *       LOCK_USED_IN_IRQ_* -> LOCK_ENABLED_IRQ_*
2540  *       LOCK_USED_IN_IRQ_*_READ -> LOCK_ENABLED_IRQ_*
2541  *       LOCK_USED_IN_IRQ_* -> LOCK_ENABLED_IRQ_*_READ
2542  *       LOCK_USED_IN_IRQ_*_READ -> LOCK_ENABLED_IRQ_*_READ
2543  *
2544  * As a result, to calculate the "exclusive mask", first we invert the
2545  * direction (USED_IN/ENABLED) of the original mask, and 1) for all bits with
2546  * bitnr0 set (LOCK_*_READ), add those with bitnr0 cleared (LOCK_*). 2) for all
2547  * bits with bitnr0 cleared (LOCK_*_READ), add those with bitnr0 set (LOCK_*).
2548  */
2549 static unsigned long exclusive_mask(unsigned long mask)
     /*   */
2550 {
2551         unsigned long excl = invert_dir_mask(mask);
2552 
2553         excl |= (excl & LOCKF_IRQ_READ) >> LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
2554         excl |= (excl & LOCKF_IRQ) << LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
2555 
2556         return excl;
2557 }
2558 
2559 /*
2560  * Retrieve the _possible_ original mask to which @mask is
2561  * exclusive. Ie: this is the opposite of exclusive_mask().
2562  * Note that 2 possible original bits can match an exclusive
2563  * bit: one has LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK set, the other has it
2564  * cleared. So both are returned for each exclusive bit.
2565  */
2566 static unsigned long original_mask(unsigned long mask)
     /*   */
2567 {
2568         unsigned long excl = invert_dir_mask(mask);
2569 
2570         /* Include read in existing usages */
2571         excl |= (excl & LOCKF_IRQ_READ) >> LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
2572         excl |= (excl & LOCKF_IRQ) << LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
2573 
2574         return excl;
2575 }
2576 
2577 /*
2578  * Find the first pair of bit match between an original
2579  * usage mask and an exclusive usage mask.
2580  */
2581 static int find_exclusive_match(unsigned long mask,
     /*   */
2582                                 unsigned long excl_mask,
2583                                 enum lock_usage_bit *bitp,
2584                                 enum lock_usage_bit *excl_bitp)
2585 {
2586         int bit, excl, excl_read;
2587 
2588         for_each_set_bit(bit, &mask, LOCK_USED) {
2589                 /*
2590                  * exclusive_bit() strips the read bit, however,
2591                  * LOCK_ENABLED_IRQ_*_READ may cause deadlocks too, so we need
2592                  * to search excl | LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK as well.
2593                  */
2594                 excl = exclusive_bit(bit);
2595                 excl_read = excl | LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
2596                 if (excl_mask & lock_flag(excl)) {
2597                         *bitp = bit;
2598                         *excl_bitp = excl;
2599                         return 0;
2600                 } else if (excl_mask & lock_flag(excl_read)) {
2601                         *bitp = bit;
2602                         *excl_bitp = excl_read;
2603                         return 0;
2604                 }
2605         }
2606         return -1;
2607 }
2608 
2609 /*
2610  * Prove that the new dependency does not connect a hardirq-safe(-read)
2611  * lock with a hardirq-unsafe lock - to achieve this we search
2612  * the backwards-subgraph starting at <prev>, and the
2613  * forwards-subgraph starting at <next>:
2614  */
2615 static int check_irq_usage(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *prev,
     /*   */
2616                            struct held_lock *next)
2617 {
2618         unsigned long usage_mask = 0, forward_mask, backward_mask;
2619         enum lock_usage_bit forward_bit = 0, backward_bit = 0;
2620         struct lock_list *target_entry1;
2621         struct lock_list *target_entry;
2622         struct lock_list this, that;
2623         enum bfs_result ret;
2624 
2625         /*
2626          * Step 1: gather all hard/soft IRQs usages backward in an
2627          * accumulated usage mask.
2628          */
2629         bfs_init_rootb(&this, prev);
2630 
2631         ret = __bfs_backwards(&this, &usage_mask, usage_accumulate, NULL);
2632         if (bfs_error(ret)) {
2633                 print_bfs_bug(ret);
2634                 return 0;
2635         }
2636 
2637         usage_mask &= LOCKF_USED_IN_IRQ_ALL;
2638         if (!usage_mask)
2639                 return 1;
2640 
2641         /*
2642          * Step 2: find exclusive uses forward that match the previous
2643          * backward accumulated mask.
2644          */
2645         forward_mask = exclusive_mask(usage_mask);
2646 
2647         bfs_init_root(&that, next);
2648 
2649         ret = find_usage_forwards(&that, forward_mask, &target_entry1);
2650         if (bfs_error(ret)) {
2651                 print_bfs_bug(ret);
2652                 return 0;
2653         }
2654         if (ret == BFS_RNOMATCH)
2655                 return 1;
2656 
2657         /*
2658          * Step 3: we found a bad match! Now retrieve a lock from the backward
2659          * list whose usage mask matches the exclusive usage mask from the
2660          * lock found on the forward list.
2661          */
2662         backward_mask = original_mask(target_entry1->class->usage_mask);
2663 
2664         ret = find_usage_backwards(&this, backward_mask, &target_entry);
2665         if (bfs_error(ret)) {
2666                 print_bfs_bug(ret);
2667                 return 0;
2668         }
2669         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(ret == BFS_RNOMATCH))
2670                 return 1;
2671 
2672         /*
2673          * Step 4: narrow down to a pair of incompatible usage bits
2674          * and report it.
2675          */
2676         ret = find_exclusive_match(target_entry->class->usage_mask,
2677                                    target_entry1->class->usage_mask,
2678                                    &backward_bit, &forward_bit);
2679         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(ret == -1))
2680                 return 1;
2681 
2682         print_bad_irq_dependency(curr, &this, &that,
2683                                  target_entry, target_entry1,
2684                                  prev, next,
2685                                  backward_bit, forward_bit,
2686                                  state_name(backward_bit));
2687 
2688         return 0;
2689 }
2690 
2691 #else
2692 
2693 static inline int check_irq_usage(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
2694                                   struct held_lock *prev, struct held_lock *next)
2695 {
2696         return 1;
2697 }
2698 #endif /* CONFIG_TRACE_IRQFLAGS */

2703                 nr_hardirq_chains++;

2705                 nr_softirq_chains++;
2706         else
2707                 nr_process_chains++;

2739 static void
2740 print_deadlock_bug(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *prev,
     /*   */
2741                    struct held_lock *next)
2742 {
2743         if (!debug_locks_off_graph_unlock() || debug_locks_silent)
2744                 return;
2745 
2746         pr_warn("\n");
2747         pr_warn("============================================\n");
2748         pr_warn("WARNING: possible recursive locking detected\n");
2749         print_kernel_ident();
2750         pr_warn("--------------------------------------------\n");
2751         pr_warn("%s/%d is trying to acquire lock:\n",
2752                 curr->comm, task_pid_nr(curr));
2753         print_lock(next);
2754         pr_warn("\nbut task is already holding lock:\n");
2755         print_lock(prev);
2756 
2757         pr_warn("\nother info that might help us debug this:\n");
2758         print_deadlock_scenario(next, prev);
2759         lockdep_print_held_locks(curr);
2760 
2761         pr_warn("\nstack backtrace:\n");
2762         dump_stack();
2763 }
2764 
2765 /*
2766  * Check whether we are holding such a class already.
2767  *
2768  * (Note that this has to be done separately, because the graph cannot
2769  * detect such classes of deadlocks.)
2770  *
2771  * Returns: 0 on deadlock detected, 1 on OK, 2 if another lock with the same
2772  * lock class is held but nest_lock is also held, i.e. we rely on the
2773  * nest_lock to avoid the deadlock.
2774  */
2775 static int
2776 check_deadlock(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *next)
     /*   */
2777 {
2778         struct held_lock *prev;
2779         struct held_lock *nest = NULL;
2780         int i;
2781 
2782         for (i = 0; i < curr->lockdep_depth; i++) {
2783                 prev = curr->held_locks + i;
2784 
2785                 if (prev->instance == next->nest_lock)
2786                         nest = prev;
2787 
2788                 if (hlock_class(prev) != hlock_class(next))
2789                         continue;
2790 
2791                 /*
2792                  * Allow read-after-read recursion of the same
2793                  * lock class (i.e. read_lock(lock)+read_lock(lock)):
2794                  */
2795                 if ((next->read == 2) && prev->read)
2796                         continue;
2797 
2798                 /*
2799                  * We're holding the nest_lock, which serializes this lock's
2800                  * nesting behaviour.
2801                  */
2802                 if (nest)
2803                         return 2;
2804 
2805                 print_deadlock_bug(curr, prev, next);
2806                 return 0;
2807         }
2808         return 1;
2809 }
2810 
2811 /*
2812  * There was a chain-cache miss, and we are about to add a new dependency
2813  * to a previous lock. We validate the following rules:
2814  *
2815  *  - would the adding of the <prev> -> <next> dependency create a
2816  *    circular dependency in the graph? [== circular deadlock]
2817  *
2818  *  - does the new prev->next dependency connect any hardirq-safe lock
2819  *    (in the full backwards-subgraph starting at <prev>) with any
2820  *    hardirq-unsafe lock (in the full forwards-subgraph starting at
2821  *    <next>)? [== illegal lock inversion with hardirq contexts]
2822  *
2823  *  - does the new prev->next dependency connect any softirq-safe lock
2824  *    (in the full backwards-subgraph starting at <prev>) with any
2825  *    softirq-unsafe lock (in the full forwards-subgraph starting at
2826  *    <next>)? [== illegal lock inversion with softirq contexts]
2827  *
2828  * any of these scenarios could lead to a deadlock.
2829  *
2830  * Then if all the validations pass, we add the forwards and backwards
2831  * dependency.
2832  */
2833 static int
2834 check_prev_add(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *prev,
     /*   */
2835                struct held_lock *next, u16 distance,
2836                struct lock_trace **const trace)
2837 {
2838         struct lock_list *entry;
2839         enum bfs_result ret;
2840 
2841         if (!hlock_class(prev)->key || !hlock_class(next)->key) {
2842                 /*
2843                  * The warning statements below may trigger a use-after-free
2844                  * of the class name. It is better to trigger a use-after free
2845                  * and to have the class name most of the time instead of not
2846                  * having the class name available.
2847                  */
2848                 WARN_ONCE(!debug_locks_silent && !hlock_class(prev)->key,
2849                           "Detected use-after-free of lock class %px/%s\n",
2850                           hlock_class(prev),
2851                           hlock_class(prev)->name);
2852                 WARN_ONCE(!debug_locks_silent && !hlock_class(next)->key,
2853                           "Detected use-after-free of lock class %px/%s\n",
2854                           hlock_class(next),
2855                           hlock_class(next)->name);
2856                 return 2;
2857         }
2858 
2859         /*
2860          * Prove that the new <prev> -> <next> dependency would not
2861          * create a circular dependency in the graph. (We do this by
2862          * a breadth-first search into the graph starting at <next>,
2863          * and check whether we can reach <prev>.)
2864          *
2865          * The search is limited by the size of the circular queue (i.e.,
2866          * MAX_CIRCULAR_QUEUE_SIZE) which keeps track of a breadth of nodes
2867          * in the graph whose neighbours are to be checked.
2868          */
2869         ret = check_noncircular(next, prev, trace);
2870         if (unlikely(bfs_error(ret) || ret == BFS_RMATCH))
2871                 return 0;
2872 
2873         if (!check_irq_usage(curr, prev, next))
2874                 return 0;
2875 
2876         /*
2877          * Is the <prev> -> <next> dependency already present?
2878          *
2879          * (this may occur even though this is a new chain: consider
2880          *  e.g. the L1 -> L2 -> L3 -> L4 and the L5 -> L1 -> L2 -> L3
2881          *  chains - the second one will be new, but L1 already has
2882          *  L2 added to its dependency list, due to the first chain.)
2883          */
2884         list_for_each_entry(entry, &hlock_class(prev)->locks_after, entry) {
2885                 if (entry->class == hlock_class(next)) {
2886                         if (distance == 1)
2887                                 entry->distance = 1;
2888                         entry->dep |= calc_dep(prev, next);
2889 
2890                         /*
2891                          * Also, update the reverse dependency in @next's
2892                          * ->locks_before list.
2893                          *
2894                          *  Here we reuse @entry as the cursor, which is fine
2895                          *  because we won't go to the next iteration of the
2896                          *  outer loop:
2897                          *
2898                          *  For normal cases, we return in the inner loop.
2899                          *
2900                          *  If we fail to return, we have inconsistency, i.e.
2901                          *  <prev>::locks_after contains <next> while
2902                          *  <next>::locks_before doesn't contain <prev>. In
2903                          *  that case, we return after the inner and indicate
2904                          *  something is wrong.
2905                          */
2906                         list_for_each_entry(entry, &hlock_class(next)->locks_before, entry) {
2907                                 if (entry->class == hlock_class(prev)) {
2908                                         if (distance == 1)
2909                                                 entry->distance = 1;
2910                                         entry->dep |= calc_depb(prev, next);
2911                                         return 1;
2912                                 }
2913                         }
2914 
2915                         /* <prev> is not found in <next>::locks_before */
2916                         return 0;
2917                 }
2918         }
2919 
2920 #ifdef CONFIG_LOCKDEP_SMALL
2921         /*
2922          * Is the <prev> -> <next> link redundant?
2923          */
2924         ret = check_redundant(prev, next);
2925         if (bfs_error(ret))
2926                 return 0;
2927         else if (ret == BFS_RMATCH)
2928                 return 2;
2929 #endif
2930 
2931         if (!*trace) {
2932                 *trace = save_trace();
2933                 if (!*trace)
2934                         return 0;
2935         }
2936 
2937         /*
2938          * Ok, all validations passed, add the new lock
2939          * to the previous lock's dependency list:
2940          */
2941         ret = add_lock_to_list(hlock_class(next), hlock_class(prev),
2942                                &hlock_class(prev)->locks_after,
2943                                next->acquire_ip, distance,
2944                                calc_dep(prev, next),
2945                                *trace);
2946 
2947         if (!ret)
2948                 return 0;
2949 
2950         ret = add_lock_to_list(hlock_class(prev), hlock_class(next),
2951                                &hlock_class(next)->locks_before,
2952                                next->acquire_ip, distance,
2953                                calc_depb(prev, next),
2954                                *trace);
2955         if (!ret)
2956                 return 0;
2957 
2958         return 2;
2959 }
2960 
2961 /*
2962  * Add the dependency to all directly-previous locks that are 'relevant'.
2963  * The ones that are relevant are (in increasing distance from curr):
2964  * all consecutive trylock entries and the final non-trylock entry - or
2965  * the end of this context's lock-chain - whichever comes first.
2966  */
2967 static int
2968 check_prevs_add(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *next)
     /*   */
2969 {
2970         struct lock_trace *trace = NULL;
2971         int depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
2972         struct held_lock *hlock;
2973 
2974         /*
2975          * Debugging checks.
2976          *
2977          * Depth must not be zero for a non-head lock:
2978          */
2979         if (!depth)
2980                 goto out_bug;
2981         /*
2982          * At least two relevant locks must exist for this
2983          * to be a head:
2984          */
2985         if (curr->held_locks[depth].irq_context !=
2986                         curr->held_locks[depth-1].irq_context)
2987                 goto out_bug;
2988 
2989         for (;;) {
2990                 u16 distance = curr->lockdep_depth - depth + 1;
2991                 hlock = curr->held_locks + depth - 1;
2992 
2993                 if (hlock->check) {
2994                         int ret = check_prev_add(curr, hlock, next, distance, &trace);
2995                         if (!ret)
2996                                 return 0;
2997 
2998                         /*
2999                          * Stop after the first non-trylock entry,
3000                          * as non-trylock entries have added their
3001                          * own direct dependencies already, so this
3002                          * lock is connected to them indirectly:
3003                          */
3004                         if (!hlock->trylock)
3005                                 break;
3006                 }
3007 
3008                 depth--;
3009                 /*
3010                  * End of lock-stack?
3011                  */
3012                 if (!depth)
3013                         break;
3014                 /*
3015                  * Stop the search if we cross into another context:
3016                  */
3017                 if (curr->held_locks[depth].irq_context !=
3018                                 curr->held_locks[depth-1].irq_context)
3019                         break;
3020         }
3021         return 1;
3022 out_bug:
3023         if (!debug_locks_off_graph_unlock())
3024                 return 0;
3025 
3026         /*
3027          * Clearly we all shouldn't be here, but since we made it we
3028          * can reliable say we messed up our state. See the above two
3029          * gotos for reasons why we could possibly end up here.
3030          */
3031         WARN_ON(1);
3032 
3033         return 0;
3034 }

3036 struct lock_chain lock_chains[MAX_LOCKDEP_CHAINS];
3037 static DECLARE_BITMAP(lock_chains_in_use, MAX_LOCKDEP_CHAINS);
3038 static u16 chain_hlocks[MAX_LOCKDEP_CHAIN_HLOCKS];
3039 unsigned long nr_zapped_lock_chains;
3040 unsigned int nr_free_chain_hlocks;      /* Free chain_hlocks in buckets */
3041 unsigned int nr_lost_chain_hlocks;      /* Lost chain_hlocks */
3042 unsigned int nr_large_chain_blocks;     /* size > MAX_CHAIN_BUCKETS */
3043 
3044 /*
3045  * The first 2 chain_hlocks entries in the chain block in the bucket
3046  * list contains the following meta data:
3047  *
3048  *   entry[0]:
3049  *     Bit    15 - always set to 1 (it is not a class index)
3050  *     Bits 0-14 - upper 15 bits of the next block index
3051  *   entry[1]    - lower 16 bits of next block index
3052  *
3053  * A next block index of all 1 bits means it is the end of the list.
3054  *
3055  * On the unsized bucket (bucket-0), the 3rd and 4th entries contain
3056  * the chain block size:
3057  *
3058  *   entry[2] - upper 16 bits of the chain block size
3059  *   entry[3] - lower 16 bits of the chain block size
3060  */
3061 #define MAX_CHAIN_BUCKETS       16
3062 #define CHAIN_BLK_FLAG          (1U << 15)
3063 #define CHAIN_BLK_LIST_END      0xFFFFU
3064 
3065 static int chain_block_buckets[MAX_CHAIN_BUCKETS];
3066 
3067 static inline int size_to_bucket(int size)
     /*   */
3068 {
3069         if (size > MAX_CHAIN_BUCKETS)
3070                 return 0;
3071 
3072         return size - 1;
3073 }
3074 
3075 /*
3076  * Iterate all the chain blocks in a bucket.
3077  */
3078 #define for_each_chain_block(bucket, prev, curr)                \
3079         for ((prev) = -1, (curr) = chain_block_buckets[bucket]; \
3080              (curr) >= 0;                                       \
3081              (prev) = (curr), (curr) = chain_block_next(curr))
3082 
3083 /*
3084  * next block or -1
3085  */
3086 static inline int chain_block_next(int offset)
     /*   */
3087 {
3088         int next = chain_hlocks[offset];
3089 
3090         WARN_ON_ONCE(!(next & CHAIN_BLK_FLAG));
3091 
3092         if (next == CHAIN_BLK_LIST_END)
3093                 return -1;
3094 
3095         next &= ~CHAIN_BLK_FLAG;
3096         next <<= 16;
3097         next |= chain_hlocks[offset + 1];
3098 
3099         return next;
3100 }
3101 
3102 /*
3103  * bucket-0 only
3104  */
3105 static inline int chain_block_size(int offset)
     /*   */
3106 {
3107         return (chain_hlocks[offset + 2] << 16) | chain_hlocks[offset + 3];
3108 }
3109 
3110 static inline void init_chain_block(int offset, int next, int bucket, int size)
     /*   */
3111 {
3112         chain_hlocks[offset] = (next >> 16) | CHAIN_BLK_FLAG;
3113         chain_hlocks[offset + 1] = (u16)next;
3114 
3115         if (size && !bucket) {
3116                 chain_hlocks[offset + 2] = size >> 16;
3117                 chain_hlocks[offset + 3] = (u16)size;
3118         }
3119 }
3120 
3121 static inline void add_chain_block(int offset, int size)
     /*   */
3122 {
3123         int bucket = size_to_bucket(size);
3124         int next = chain_block_buckets[bucket];
3125         int prev, curr;
3126 
3127         if (unlikely(size < 2)) {
3128                 /*
3129                  * We can't store single entries on the freelist. Leak them.
3130                  *
3131                  * One possible way out would be to uniquely mark them, other
3132                  * than with CHAIN_BLK_FLAG, such that we can recover them when
3133                  * the block before it is re-added.
3134                  */
3135                 if (size)
3136                         nr_lost_chain_hlocks++;
3137                 return;
3138         }
3139 
3140         nr_free_chain_hlocks += size;
3141         if (!bucket) {
3142                 nr_large_chain_blocks++;
3143 
3144                 /*
3145                  * Variable sized, sort large to small.
3146                  */
3147                 for_each_chain_block(0, prev, curr) {
3148                         if (size >= chain_block_size(curr))
3149                                 break;
3150                 }
3151                 init_chain_block(offset, curr, 0, size);
3152                 if (prev < 0)
3153                         chain_block_buckets[0] = offset;
3154                 else
3155                         init_chain_block(prev, offset, 0, 0);
3156                 return;
3157         }
3158         /*
3159          * Fixed size, add to head.
3160          */
3161         init_chain_block(offset, next, bucket, size);
3162         chain_block_buckets[bucket] = offset;
3163 }
3164 
3165 /*
3166  * Only the first block in the list can be deleted.
3167  *
3168  * For the variable size bucket[0], the first block (the largest one) is
3169  * returned, broken up and put back into the pool. So if a chain block of
3170  * length > MAX_CHAIN_BUCKETS is ever used and zapped, it will just be
3171  * queued up after the primordial chain block and never be used until the
3172  * hlock entries in the primordial chain block is almost used up. That
3173  * causes fragmentation and reduce allocation efficiency. That can be
3174  * monitored by looking at the "large chain blocks" number in lockdep_stats.
3175  */
3176 static inline void del_chain_block(int bucket, int size, int next)
     /*   */
3177 {
3178         nr_free_chain_hlocks -= size;
3179         chain_block_buckets[bucket] = next;
3180 
3181         if (!bucket)
3182                 nr_large_chain_blocks--;
3183 }
3184 
3185 static void init_chain_block_buckets(void)
     /*   */
3186 {
3187         int i;
3188 
3189         for (i = 0; i < MAX_CHAIN_BUCKETS; i++)
3190                 chain_block_buckets[i] = -1;
3191 
3192         add_chain_block(0, ARRAY_SIZE(chain_hlocks));
3193 }
3194 
3195 /*
3196  * Return offset of a chain block of the right size or -1 if not found.
3197  *
3198  * Fairly simple worst-fit allocator with the addition of a number of size
3199  * specific free lists.
3200  */
3201 static int alloc_chain_hlocks(int req)
     /*   */
3202 {
3203         int bucket, curr, size;
3204 
3205         /*
3206          * We rely on the MSB to act as an escape bit to denote freelist
3207          * pointers. Make sure this bit isn't set in 'normal' class_idx usage.
3208          */
3209         BUILD_BUG_ON((MAX_LOCKDEP_KEYS-1) & CHAIN_BLK_FLAG);
3210 
3211         init_data_structures_once();
3212 
3213         if (nr_free_chain_hlocks < req)
3214                 return -1;
3215 
3216         /*
3217          * We require a minimum of 2 (u16) entries to encode a freelist
3218          * 'pointer'.
3219          */
3220         req = max(req, 2);
3221         bucket = size_to_bucket(req);
3222         curr = chain_block_buckets[bucket];
3223 
3224         if (bucket) {
3225                 if (curr >= 0) {
3226                         del_chain_block(bucket, req, chain_block_next(curr));
3227                         return curr;
3228                 }
3229                 /* Try bucket 0 */
3230                 curr = chain_block_buckets[0];
3231         }
3232 
3233         /*
3234          * The variable sized freelist is sorted by size; the first entry is
3235          * the largest. Use it if it fits.
3236          */
3237         if (curr >= 0) {
3238                 size = chain_block_size(curr);
3239                 if (likely(size >= req)) {
3240                         del_chain_block(0, size, chain_block_next(curr));
3241                         add_chain_block(curr + req, size - req);
3242                         return curr;
3243                 }
3244         }
3245 
3246         /*
3247          * Last resort, split a block in a larger sized bucket.
3248          */
3249         for (size = MAX_CHAIN_BUCKETS; size > req; size--) {
3250                 bucket = size_to_bucket(size);
3251                 curr = chain_block_buckets[bucket];
3252                 if (curr < 0)
3253                         continue;
3254 
3255                 del_chain_block(bucket, size, chain_block_next(curr));
3256                 add_chain_block(curr + req, size - req);
3257                 return curr;
3258         }
3259 
3260         return -1;
3261 }
3262 
3263 static inline void free_chain_hlocks(int base, int size)
     /*   */
3264 {
3265         add_chain_block(base, max(size, 2));
3266 }

     /*   */

3271         unsigned int class_idx = chain_hlock_class_idx(chain_hlock);

3274 }

3278  */

     /*   */
3280                                         struct held_lock *hlock)
3281 {
3282         int i;

3286                 hlock_curr = curr->held_locks + i;

3288                         break;
3289

3369 /*
3370  * Checks whether the chain and the current held locks are consistent
3371  * in depth and also in content. If they are not it most likely means
3372  * that there was a collision during the calculation of the chain_key.
3373  * Returns: 0 not passed, 1 passed
3374  */
3375 static int check_no_collision(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
3376                         struct held_lock *hlock,
3377                         struct lock_chain *chain)
3378 {
3379 #ifdef CONFIG_DEBUG_LOCKDEP
3380         int i, j, id;
3381 
3382         i = get_first_held_lock(curr, hlock);
3383 
3384         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(chain->depth != curr->lockdep_depth - (i - 1))) {
3385                 print_collision(curr, hlock, chain);
3386                 return 0;
3387         }
3388 
3389         for (j = 0; j < chain->depth - 1; j++, i++) {
3390                 id = hlock_id(&curr->held_locks[i]);
3391 
3392                 if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(chain_hlocks[chain->base + j] != id)) {
3393                         print_collision(curr, hlock, chain);
3394                         return 0;
3395                 }
3396         }
3397 #endif
3398         return 1;
3399 }

3416 /* Must be called with the graph lock held. */
3417 static struct lock_chain *alloc_lock_chain(void)
     /*   */
3418 {

3420                                       ARRAY_SIZE(lock_chains));
3421

3423                 return NULL;

3428 /*
3429  * Adds a dependency chain into chain hashtable. And must be called with
3430  * graph_lock held.
3431  *
3432  * Return 0 if fail, and graph_lock is released.
3433  * Return 1 if succeed, with graph_lock held.
3434  */
3435 static inline int add_chain_cache(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
3436                                   struct held_lock *hlock,
3437                                   u64 chain_key)
3438 {
3439         struct hlist_head *hash_head = chainhashentry(chain_key);
3440         struct lock_chain *chain;
3441         int i, j;
3442 
3443         /*
3444          * The caller must hold the graph lock, ensure we've got IRQs
3445          * disabled to make this an IRQ-safe lock.. for recursion reasons
3446          * lockdep won't complain about its own locking errors.
3447          */
3448         if (lockdep_assert_locked())
3449                 return 0;
3450 
3451         chain = alloc_lock_chain();
3452         if (!chain) {
3453                 if (!debug_locks_off_graph_unlock())
3454                         return 0;
3455 
3456                 print_lockdep_off("BUG: MAX_LOCKDEP_CHAINS too low!");
3457                 dump_stack();
3458                 return 0;
3459         }
3460         chain->chain_key = chain_key;
3461         chain->irq_context = hlock->irq_context;
3462         i = get_first_held_lock(curr, hlock);
3463         chain->depth = curr->lockdep_depth + 1 - i;
3464 
3465         BUILD_BUG_ON((1UL << 24) <= ARRAY_SIZE(chain_hlocks));
3466         BUILD_BUG_ON((1UL << 6)  <= ARRAY_SIZE(curr->held_locks));
3467         BUILD_BUG_ON((1UL << 8*sizeof(chain_hlocks[0])) <= ARRAY_SIZE(lock_classes));
3468 
3469         j = alloc_chain_hlocks(chain->depth);
3470         if (j < 0) {
3471                 if (!debug_locks_off_graph_unlock())
3472                         return 0;
3473 
3474                 print_lockdep_off("BUG: MAX_LOCKDEP_CHAIN_HLOCKS too low!");
3475                 dump_stack();
3476                 return 0;
3477         }
3478 
3479         chain->base = j;
3480         for (j = 0; j < chain->depth - 1; j++, i++) {
3481                 int lock_id = hlock_id(curr->held_locks + i);
3482 
3483                 chain_hlocks[chain->base + j] = lock_id;
3484         }
3485         chain_hlocks[chain->base + j] = hlock_id(hlock);
3486         hlist_add_head_rcu(&chain->entry, hash_head);
3487         debug_atomic_inc(chain_lookup_misses);
3488         inc_chains(chain->irq_context);
3489 
3490         return 1;
3491 }
3492 
3493 /*
3494  * Look up a dependency chain. Must be called with either the graph lock or
3495  * the RCU read lock held.
3496  */
3497 static inline struct lock_chain *lookup_chain_cache(u64 chain_key)
     /*   */
3498 {
3499         struct hlist_head *hash_head = chainhashentry(chain_key);
3500         struct lock_chain *chain;
3501 
3502         hlist_for_each_entry_rcu(chain, hash_head, entry) {
3503                 if (READ_ONCE(chain->chain_key) == chain_key) {
3504                         debug_atomic_inc(chain_lookup_hits);
3505                         return chain;
3506                 }
3507         }
3508         return NULL;
3509 }
3510 
3511 /*
3512  * If the key is not present yet in dependency chain cache then
3513  * add it and return 1 - in this case the new dependency chain is
3514  * validated. If the key is already hashed, return 0.
3515  * (On return with 1 graph_lock is held.)
3516  */
3517 static inline int lookup_chain_cache_add(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
3518                                          struct held_lock *hlock,
3519                                          u64 chain_key)
3520 {
3521         struct lock_class *class = hlock_class(hlock);
3522         struct lock_chain *chain = lookup_chain_cache(chain_key);
3523 
3524         if (chain) {
3525 cache_hit:
3526                 if (!check_no_collision(curr, hlock, chain))
3527                         return 0;
3528 
3529                 if (very_verbose(class)) {
3530                         printk("\nhash chain already cached, key: "
3531                                         "%016Lx tail class: [%px] %s\n",
3532                                         (unsigned long long)chain_key,
3533                                         class->key, class->name);
3534                 }
3535 
3536                 return 0;
3537         }
3538 
3539         if (very_verbose(class)) {
3540                 printk("\nnew hash chain, key: %016Lx tail class: [%px] %s\n",
3541                         (unsigned long long)chain_key, class->key, class->name);
3542         }
3543 
3544         if (!graph_lock())
3545                 return 0;
3546 
3547         /*
3548          * We have to walk the chain again locked - to avoid duplicates:
3549          */
3550         chain = lookup_chain_cache(chain_key);
3551         if (chain) {
3552                 graph_unlock();
3553                 goto cache_hit;
3554         }
3555 
3556         if (!add_chain_cache(curr, hlock, chain_key))
3557                 return 0;
3558 
3559         return 1;
3560 }
3561 
3562 static int validate_chain(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
3563                           struct held_lock *hlock,
3564                           int chain_head, u64 chain_key)
3565 {
3566         /*
3567          * Trylock needs to maintain the stack of held locks, but it
3568          * does not add new dependencies, because trylock can be done
3569          * in any order.
3570          *
3571          * We look up the chain_key and do the O(N^2) check and update of
3572          * the dependencies only if this is a new dependency chain.
3573          * (If lookup_chain_cache_add() return with 1 it acquires
3574          * graph_lock for us)
3575          */
3576         if (!hlock->trylock && hlock->check &&
3577             lookup_chain_cache_add(curr, hlock, chain_key)) {
3578                 /*
3579                  * Check whether last held lock:
3580                  *
3581                  * - is irq-safe, if this lock is irq-unsafe
3582                  * - is softirq-safe, if this lock is hardirq-unsafe
3583                  *
3584                  * And check whether the new lock's dependency graph
3585                  * could lead back to the previous lock:
3586                  *
3587                  * - within the current held-lock stack
3588                  * - across our accumulated lock dependency records
3589                  *
3590                  * any of these scenarios could lead to a deadlock.
3591                  */
3592                 /*
3593                  * The simple case: does the current hold the same lock
3594                  * already?
3595                  */
3596                 int ret = check_deadlock(curr, hlock);
3597 
3598                 if (!ret)
3599                         return 0;
3600                 /*
3601                  * Add dependency only if this lock is not the head
3602                  * of the chain, and if the new lock introduces no more
3603                  * lock dependency (because we already hold a lock with the
3604                  * same lock class) nor deadlock (because the nest_lock
3605                  * serializes nesting locks), see the comments for
3606                  * check_deadlock().
3607                  */
3608                 if (!chain_head && ret != 2) {
3609                         if (!check_prevs_add(curr, hlock))
3610                                 return 0;
3611                 }
3612 
3613                 graph_unlock();
3614         } else {
3615                 /* after lookup_chain_cache_add(): */
3616                 if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
3617                         return 0;
3618         }
3619 
3620         return 1;
3621 }
3622 #else
3623 static inline int validate_chain(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
3624                                  struct held_lock *hlock,
3625                                  int chain_head, u64 chain_key)
3626 {
3627         return 1;
3628 }

3633 /*
3634  * We are building curr_chain_key incrementally, so double-check
3635  * it from scratch, to make sure that it's done correctly:
3636  */
3637 static void check_chain_key(struct task_struct *curr)
     /*   */
3638 {
3639 #ifdef CONFIG_DEBUG_LOCKDEP
3640         struct held_lock *hlock, *prev_hlock = NULL;
3641         unsigned int i;
3642         u64 chain_key = INITIAL_CHAIN_KEY;
3643 
3644         for (i = 0; i < curr->lockdep_depth; i++) {
3645                 hlock = curr->held_locks + i;
3646                 if (chain_key != hlock->prev_chain_key) {
3647                         debug_locks_off();
3648                         /*
3649                          * We got mighty confused, our chain keys don't match
3650                          * with what we expect, someone trample on our task state?
3651                          */
3652                         WARN(1, "hm#1, depth: %u [%u], %016Lx != %016Lx\n",
3653                                 curr->lockdep_depth, i,
3654                                 (unsigned long long)chain_key,
3655                                 (unsigned long long)hlock->prev_chain_key);
3656                         return;
3657                 }
3658 
3659                 /*
3660                  * hlock->class_idx can't go beyond MAX_LOCKDEP_KEYS, but is
3661                  * it registered lock class index?
3662                  */
3663                 if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!test_bit(hlock->class_idx, lock_classes_in_use)))
3664                         return;
3665 
3666                 if (prev_hlock && (prev_hlock->irq_context !=
3667                                                         hlock->irq_context))
3668                         chain_key = INITIAL_CHAIN_KEY;
3669                 chain_key = iterate_chain_key(chain_key, hlock_id(hlock));
3670                 prev_hlock = hlock;
3671         }
3672         if (chain_key != curr->curr_chain_key) {
3673                 debug_locks_off();
3674                 /*
3675                  * More smoking hash instead of calculating it, damn see these
3676                  * numbers float.. I bet that a pink elephant stepped on my memory.
3677                  */
3678                 WARN(1, "hm#2, depth: %u [%u], %016Lx != %016Lx\n",
3679                         curr->lockdep_depth, i,
3680                         (unsigned long long)chain_key,
3681                         (unsigned long long)curr->curr_chain_key);
3682         }
3683 #endif
3684 }

3707 static void
3708 print_usage_bug(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *this,
     /*   */
3709                 enum lock_usage_bit prev_bit, enum lock_usage_bit new_bit)
3710 {
3711         if (!debug_locks_off() || debug_locks_silent)
3712                 return;
3713

3715         pr_warn("================================\n");

3721                 usage_str[prev_bit], usage_str[new_bit]);

3724                 curr->comm, task_pid_nr(curr),
3725                 lockdep_hardirq_context(), hardirq_count() >> HARDIRQ_SHIFT,
3726                 lockdep_softirq_context(curr), softirq_count() >> SOFTIRQ_SHIFT,
3727                 lockdep_hardirqs_enabled(),
3728                 lockdep_softirqs_enabled(curr));
3729         print_lock(this);
3730 
3731         pr_warn("{%s} state was registered at:\n", usage_str[prev_bit]);
3732         print_lock_trace(hlock_class(this)->usage_traces[prev_bit], 1);
3733 
3734         print_irqtrace_events(curr);
3735         pr_warn("\nother info that might help us debug this:\n");
3736         print_usage_bug_scenario(this);
3737 
3738         lockdep_print_held_locks(curr);
3739 
3740         pr_warn("\nstack backtrace:\n");
3741         dump_stack();

3744 /*
3745  * Print out an error if an invalid bit is set:
3746  */
3747 static inline int
3748 valid_state(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *this,
     /*   */
3749             enum lock_usage_bit new_bit, enum lock_usage_bit bad_bit)
3750 {
3751         if (unlikely(hlock_class(this)->usage_mask & (1 << bad_bit))) {
3752                 graph_unlock();
3753                 print_usage_bug(curr, this, bad_bit, new_bit);
3754                 return 0;
3755         }
3756         return 1;
3757 }

3760 /*
3761  * print irq inversion bug:
3762  */
3763 static void
3764 print_irq_inversion_bug(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
3765                         struct lock_list *root, struct lock_list *other,
3766                         struct held_lock *this, int forwards,
3767                         const char *irqclass)
3768 {
3769         struct lock_list *entry = other;
3770         struct lock_list *middle = NULL;
3771         int depth;
3772 
3773         if (!debug_locks_off_graph_unlock() || debug_locks_silent)
3774                 return;
3775 
3776         pr_warn("\n");
3777         pr_warn("========================================================\n");
3778         pr_warn("WARNING: possible irq lock inversion dependency detected\n");
3779         print_kernel_ident();
3780         pr_warn("--------------------------------------------------------\n");
3781         pr_warn("%s/%d just changed the state of lock:\n",
3782                 curr->comm, task_pid_nr(curr));
3783         print_lock(this);
3784         if (forwards)
3785                 pr_warn("but this lock took another, %s-unsafe lock in the past:\n", irqclass);
3786         else
3787                 pr_warn("but this lock was taken by another, %s-safe lock in the past:\n", irqclass);
3788         print_lock_name(other->class);
3789         pr_warn("\n\nand interrupts could create inverse lock ordering between them.\n\n");
3790 
3791         pr_warn("\nother info that might help us debug this:\n");
3792 
3793         /* Find a middle lock (if one exists) */
3794         depth = get_lock_depth(other);
3795         do {
3796                 if (depth == 0 && (entry != root)) {
3797                         pr_warn("lockdep:%s bad path found in chain graph\n", __func__);
3798                         break;
3799                 }
3800                 middle = entry;
3801                 entry = get_lock_parent(entry);
3802                 depth--;
3803         } while (entry && entry != root && (depth >= 0));
3804         if (forwards)
3805                 print_irq_lock_scenario(root, other,
3806                         middle ? middle->class : root->class, other->class);
3807         else
3808                 print_irq_lock_scenario(other, root,
3809                         middle ? middle->class : other->class, root->class);
3810 
3811         lockdep_print_held_locks(curr);
3812 
3813         pr_warn("\nthe shortest dependencies between 2nd lock and 1st lock:\n");
3814         root->trace = save_trace();
3815         if (!root->trace)
3816                 return;
3817         print_shortest_lock_dependencies(other, root);
3818 
3819         pr_warn("\nstack backtrace:\n");
3820         dump_stack();
3821 }

3823 /*
3824  * Prove that in the forwards-direction subgraph starting at <this>
3825  * there is no lock matching <mask>:
3826  */
3827 static int
3828 check_usage_forwards(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *this,
     /*   */
3829                      enum lock_usage_bit bit)
3830 {
3831         enum bfs_result ret;
3832         struct lock_list root;
3833         struct lock_list *target_entry;
3834         enum lock_usage_bit read_bit = bit + LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
3835         unsigned usage_mask = lock_flag(bit) | lock_flag(read_bit);
3836 
3837         bfs_init_root(&root, this);
3838         ret = find_usage_forwards(&root, usage_mask, &target_entry);
3839         if (bfs_error(ret)) {
3840                 print_bfs_bug(ret);
3841                 return 0;
3842         }
3843         if (ret == BFS_RNOMATCH)
3844                 return 1;
3845 
3846         /* Check whether write or read usage is the match */
3847         if (target_entry->class->usage_mask & lock_flag(bit)) {
3848                 print_irq_inversion_bug(curr, &root, target_entry,
3849                                         this, 1, state_name(bit));
3850         } else {
3851                 print_irq_inversion_bug(curr, &root, target_entry,
3852                                         this, 1, state_name(read_bit));
3853         }
3854 
3855         return 0;
3856 }
3857 
3858 /*
3859  * Prove that in the backwards-direction subgraph starting at <this>
3860  * there is no lock matching <mask>:
3861  */
3862 static int
3863 check_usage_backwards(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *this,
     /*   */
3864                       enum lock_usage_bit bit)
3865 {
3866         enum bfs_result ret;
3867         struct lock_list root;
3868         struct lock_list *target_entry;
3869         enum lock_usage_bit read_bit = bit + LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
3870         unsigned usage_mask = lock_flag(bit) | lock_flag(read_bit);
3871 
3872         bfs_init_rootb(&root, this);
3873         ret = find_usage_backwards(&root, usage_mask, &target_entry);
3874         if (bfs_error(ret)) {
3875                 print_bfs_bug(ret);
3876                 return 0;
3877         }
3878         if (ret == BFS_RNOMATCH)
3879                 return 1;
3880 
3881         /* Check whether write or read usage is the match */
3882         if (target_entry->class->usage_mask & lock_flag(bit)) {
3883                 print_irq_inversion_bug(curr, &root, target_entry,
3884                                         this, 0, state_name(bit));
3885         } else {
3886                 print_irq_inversion_bug(curr, &root, target_entry,
3887                                         this, 0, state_name(read_bit));
3888         }
3889 
3890         return 0;
3891 }

     /*   */
3936                                 struct lock_class *class)

3941 typedef int (*check_usage_f)(struct task_struct *, struct held_lock *,
3942                              enum lock_usage_bit bit, const char *name);

3944 static int
3945 mark_lock_irq(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *this,
     /*   */
3946                 enum lock_usage_bit new_bit)
3947 {
3948         int excl_bit = exclusive_bit(new_bit);
3949         int read = new_bit & LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
3950         int dir = new_bit & LOCK_USAGE_DIR_MASK;
3951 
3952         /*
3953          * Validate that this particular lock does not have conflicting
3954          * usage states.
3955          */
3956         if (!valid_state(curr, this, new_bit, excl_bit))
3957                 return 0;
3958 
3959         /*
3960          * Check for read in write conflicts
3961          */
3962         if (!read && !valid_state(curr, this, new_bit,
3963                                   excl_bit + LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK))
3964                 return 0;
3965 
3966 
3967         /*
3968          * Validate that the lock dependencies don't have conflicting usage
3969          * states.
3970          */
3971         if (dir) {
3972                 /*
3973                  * mark ENABLED has to look backwards -- to ensure no dependee
3974                  * has USED_IN state, which, again, would allow  recursion deadlocks.
3975                  */
3976                 if (!check_usage_backwards(curr, this, excl_bit))
3977                         return 0;
3978         } else {
3979                 /*
3980                  * mark USED_IN has to look forwards -- to ensure no dependency
3981                  * has ENABLED state, which would allow recursion deadlocks.
3982                  */
3983                 if (!check_usage_forwards(curr, this, excl_bit))
3984                         return 0;
3985         }
3986 
3987         if (state_verbose(new_bit, hlock_class(this)))
3988                 return 2;
3989 
3990         return 1;
3991 }

3993 /*
3994  * Mark all held locks with a usage bit:
3995  */
3996 static int
3997 mark_held_locks(struct task_struct *curr, enum lock_usage_bit base_bit)
     /*   */
3998 {
3999         struct held_lock *hlock;
4000         int i;
4001 
4002         for (i = 0; i < curr->lockdep_depth; i++) {
4003                 enum lock_usage_bit hlock_bit = base_bit;
4004                 hlock = curr->held_locks + i;
4005 
4006                 if (hlock->read)
4007                         hlock_bit += LOCK_USAGE_READ_MASK;
4008 
4009                 BUG_ON(hlock_bit >= LOCK_USAGE_STATES);
4010 
4011                 if (!hlock->check)
4012                         continue;
4013 
4014                 if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock, hlock_bit))
4015                         return 0;
4016         }
4017 
4018         return 1;
4019 }

4021 /*
4022  * Hardirqs will be enabled:
4023  */
4024 static void __trace_hardirqs_on_caller(void)
     /*   */
4025 {
4026         struct task_struct *curr = current;
4027 
4028         /*
4029          * We are going to turn hardirqs on, so set the
4030          * usage bit for all held locks:
4031          */
4032         if (!mark_held_locks(curr, LOCK_ENABLED_HARDIRQ))
4033                 return;
4034         /*
4035          * If we have softirqs enabled, then set the usage
4036          * bit for all held locks. (disabled hardirqs prevented
4037          * this bit from being set before)
4038          */
4039         if (curr->softirqs_enabled)
4040                 mark_held_locks(curr, LOCK_ENABLED_SOFTIRQ);
4041 }

4043 /**
4044  * lockdep_hardirqs_on_prepare - Prepare for enabling interrupts
4045  * @ip:         Caller address
4046  *
4047  * Invoked before a possible transition to RCU idle from exit to user or
4048  * guest mode. This ensures that all RCU operations are done before RCU
4049  * stops watching. After the RCU transition lockdep_hardirqs_on() has to be
4050  * invoked to set the final state.
4051  */
4052 void lockdep_hardirqs_on_prepare(unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
4053 {
4054         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
4055                 return;
4056 
4057         /*
4058          * NMIs do not (and cannot) track lock dependencies, nothing to do.
4059          */
4060         if (unlikely(in_nmi()))
4061                 return;
4062 
4063         if (unlikely(this_cpu_read(lockdep_recursion)))
4064                 return;
4065 
4066         if (unlikely(lockdep_hardirqs_enabled())) {
4067                 /*
4068                  * Neither irq nor preemption are disabled here
4069                  * so this is racy by nature but losing one hit
4070                  * in a stat is not a big deal.
4071                  */
4072                 __debug_atomic_inc(redundant_hardirqs_on);
4073                 return;
4074         }
4075 
4076         /*
4077          * We're enabling irqs and according to our state above irqs weren't
4078          * already enabled, yet we find the hardware thinks they are in fact
4079          * enabled.. someone messed up their IRQ state tracing.
4080          */
4081         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!irqs_disabled()))
4082                 return;
4083 
4084         /*
4085          * See the fine text that goes along with this variable definition.
4086          */
4087         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(early_boot_irqs_disabled))
4088                 return;
4089 
4090         /*
4091          * Can't allow enabling interrupts while in an interrupt handler,
4092          * that's general bad form and such. Recursion, limited stack etc..
4093          */
4094         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(lockdep_hardirq_context()))
4095                 return;
4096 
4097         current->hardirq_chain_key = current->curr_chain_key;
4098 
4099         lockdep_recursion_inc();
4100         __trace_hardirqs_on_caller();
4101         lockdep_recursion_finish();
4102 }
4103 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(lockdep_hardirqs_on_prepare);
4104 
4105 void noinstr lockdep_hardirqs_on(unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
4106 {
4107         struct irqtrace_events *trace = &current->irqtrace;
4108 
4109         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
4110                 return;
4111 
4112         /*
4113          * NMIs can happen in the middle of local_irq_{en,dis}able() where the
4114          * tracking state and hardware state are out of sync.
4115          *
4116          * NMIs must save lockdep_hardirqs_enabled() to restore IRQ state from,
4117          * and not rely on hardware state like normal interrupts.
4118          */
4119         if (unlikely(in_nmi())) {
4120                 if (!IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_TRACE_IRQFLAGS_NMI))
4121                         return;
4122 
4123                 /*
4124                  * Skip:
4125                  *  - recursion check, because NMI can hit lockdep;
4126                  *  - hardware state check, because above;
4127                  *  - chain_key check, see lockdep_hardirqs_on_prepare().
4128                  */
4129                 goto skip_checks;
4130         }
4131 
4132         if (unlikely(this_cpu_read(lockdep_recursion)))
4133                 return;
4134 
4135         if (lockdep_hardirqs_enabled()) {
4136                 /*
4137                  * Neither irq nor preemption are disabled here
4138                  * so this is racy by nature but losing one hit
4139                  * in a stat is not a big deal.
4140                  */
4141                 __debug_atomic_inc(redundant_hardirqs_on);
4142                 return;
4143         }
4144 
4145         /*
4146          * We're enabling irqs and according to our state above irqs weren't
4147          * already enabled, yet we find the hardware thinks they are in fact
4148          * enabled.. someone messed up their IRQ state tracing.
4149          */
4150         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!irqs_disabled()))
4151                 return;
4152 
4153         /*
4154          * Ensure the lock stack remained unchanged between
4155          * lockdep_hardirqs_on_prepare() and lockdep_hardirqs_on().
4156          */
4157         DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(current->hardirq_chain_key !=
4158                             current->curr_chain_key);
4159 
4160 skip_checks:
4161         /* we'll do an OFF -> ON transition: */
4162         __this_cpu_write(hardirqs_enabled, 1);
4163         trace->hardirq_enable_ip = ip;
4164         trace->hardirq_enable_event = ++trace->irq_events;
4165         debug_atomic_inc(hardirqs_on_events);
4166 }
4167 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(lockdep_hardirqs_on);
4168 
4169 /*
4170  * Hardirqs were disabled:
4171  */
4172 void noinstr lockdep_hardirqs_off(unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
4173 {
4174         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
4175                 return;
4176 
4177         /*
4178          * Matching lockdep_hardirqs_on(), allow NMIs in the middle of lockdep;
4179          * they will restore the software state. This ensures the software
4180          * state is consistent inside NMIs as well.
4181          */
4182         if (in_nmi()) {
4183                 if (!IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_TRACE_IRQFLAGS_NMI))
4184                         return;
4185         } else if (__this_cpu_read(lockdep_recursion))
4186                 return;
4187 
4188         /*
4189          * So we're supposed to get called after you mask local IRQs, but for
4190          * some reason the hardware doesn't quite think you did a proper job.
4191          */
4192         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!irqs_disabled()))
4193                 return;
4194 
4195         if (lockdep_hardirqs_enabled()) {
4196                 struct irqtrace_events *trace = &current->irqtrace;
4197 
4198                 /*
4199                  * We have done an ON -> OFF transition:
4200                  */
4201                 __this_cpu_write(hardirqs_enabled, 0);
4202                 trace->hardirq_disable_ip = ip;
4203                 trace->hardirq_disable_event = ++trace->irq_events;
4204                 debug_atomic_inc(hardirqs_off_events);
4205         } else {
4206                 debug_atomic_inc(redundant_hardirqs_off);
4207         }
4208 }
4209 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(lockdep_hardirqs_off);
4210 
4211 /*
4212  * Softirqs will be enabled:
4213  */
4214 void lockdep_softirqs_on(unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
4215 {
4216         struct irqtrace_events *trace = &current->irqtrace;
4217 
4218         if (unlikely(!lockdep_enabled()))
4219                 return;
4220 
4221         /*
4222          * We fancy IRQs being disabled here, see softirq.c, avoids
4223          * funny state and nesting things.
4224          */
4225         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!irqs_disabled()))
4226                 return;
4227 
4228         if (current->softirqs_enabled) {
4229                 debug_atomic_inc(redundant_softirqs_on);
4230                 return;
4231         }
4232 
4233         lockdep_recursion_inc();
4234         /*
4235          * We'll do an OFF -> ON transition:
4236          */
4237         current->softirqs_enabled = 1;
4238         trace->softirq_enable_ip = ip;
4239         trace->softirq_enable_event = ++trace->irq_events;
4240         debug_atomic_inc(softirqs_on_events);
4241         /*
4242          * We are going to turn softirqs on, so set the
4243          * usage bit for all held locks, if hardirqs are
4244          * enabled too:
4245          */
4246         if (lockdep_hardirqs_enabled())
4247                 mark_held_locks(current, LOCK_ENABLED_SOFTIRQ);
4248         lockdep_recursion_finish();
4249 }

4251 /*
4252  * Softirqs were disabled:
4253  */
4254 void lockdep_softirqs_off(unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
4255 {
4256         if (unlikely(!lockdep_enabled()))
4257                 return;
4258 
4259         /*
4260          * We fancy IRQs being disabled here, see softirq.c
4261          */
4262         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!irqs_disabled()))
4263                 return;
4264 
4265         if (current->softirqs_enabled) {
4266                 struct irqtrace_events *trace = &current->irqtrace;
4267 
4268                 /*
4269                  * We have done an ON -> OFF transition:
4270                  */
4271                 current->softirqs_enabled = 0;
4272                 trace->softirq_disable_ip = ip;
4273                 trace->softirq_disable_event = ++trace->irq_events;
4274                 debug_atomic_inc(softirqs_off_events);
4275                 /*
4276                  * Whoops, we wanted softirqs off, so why aren't they?
4277                  */
4278                 DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!softirq_count());
4279         } else
4280                 debug_atomic_inc(redundant_softirqs_off);
4281 }
4282 
4283 static int
4284 mark_usage(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *hlock, int check)
     /*   */
4285 {
4286         if (!check)
4287                 goto lock_used;
4288 
4289         /*
4290          * If non-trylock use in a hardirq or softirq context, then
4291          * mark the lock as used in these contexts:
4292          */
4293         if (!hlock->trylock) {
4294                 if (hlock->read) {
4295                         if (lockdep_hardirq_context())
4296                                 if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock,
4297                                                 LOCK_USED_IN_HARDIRQ_READ))
4298                                         return 0;
4299                         if (curr->softirq_context)
4300                                 if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock,
4301                                                 LOCK_USED_IN_SOFTIRQ_READ))
4302                                         return 0;
4303                 } else {
4304                         if (lockdep_hardirq_context())
4305                                 if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock, LOCK_USED_IN_HARDIRQ))
4306                                         return 0;
4307                         if (curr->softirq_context)
4308                                 if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock, LOCK_USED_IN_SOFTIRQ))
4309                                         return 0;
4310                 }
4311         }
4312         if (!hlock->hardirqs_off) {
4313                 if (hlock->read) {
4314                         if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock,
4315                                         LOCK_ENABLED_HARDIRQ_READ))
4316                                 return 0;
4317                         if (curr->softirqs_enabled)
4318                                 if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock,
4319                                                 LOCK_ENABLED_SOFTIRQ_READ))
4320                                         return 0;
4321                 } else {
4322                         if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock,
4323                                         LOCK_ENABLED_HARDIRQ))
4324                                 return 0;
4325                         if (curr->softirqs_enabled)
4326                                 if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock,
4327                                                 LOCK_ENABLED_SOFTIRQ))
4328                                         return 0;
4329                 }
4330         }
4331 
4332 lock_used:
4333         /* mark it as used: */
4334         if (!mark_lock(curr, hlock, LOCK_USED))
4335                 return 0;
4336 
4337         return 1;
4338 }

4340 static inline unsigned int task_irq_context(struct task_struct *task)
     /*   */
4341 {
4342         return LOCK_CHAIN_HARDIRQ_CONTEXT * !!lockdep_hardirq_context() +
4343                LOCK_CHAIN_SOFTIRQ_CONTEXT * !!task->softirq_context;
4344 }
4345 
4346 static int separate_irq_context(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
4347                 struct held_lock *hlock)
4348 {
4349         unsigned int depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
4350 
4351         /*
4352          * Keep track of points where we cross into an interrupt context:
4353          */
4354         if (depth) {
4355                 struct held_lock *prev_hlock;
4356 
4357                 prev_hlock = curr->held_locks + depth-1;
4358                 /*
4359                  * If we cross into another context, reset the
4360                  * hash key (this also prevents the checking and the
4361                  * adding of the dependency to 'prev'):
4362                  */
4363                 if (prev_hlock->irq_context != hlock->irq_context)
4364                         return 1;
4365         }
4366         return 0;
4367 }

4369 /*
4370  * Mark a lock with a usage bit, and validate the state transition:
4371  */
4372 static int mark_lock(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *this,
     /*   */
4373                              enum lock_usage_bit new_bit)
4374 {
4375         unsigned int new_mask, ret = 1;
4376 
4377         if (new_bit >= LOCK_USAGE_STATES) {
4378                 DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(1);
4379                 return 0;
4380         }
4381 
4382         if (new_bit == LOCK_USED && this->read)
4383                 new_bit = LOCK_USED_READ;
4384 
4385         new_mask = 1 << new_bit;
4386 
4387         /*
4388          * If already set then do not dirty the cacheline,
4389          * nor do any checks:
4390          */
4391         if (likely(hlock_class(this)->usage_mask & new_mask))
4392                 return 1;
4393 
4394         if (!graph_lock())
4395                 return 0;
4396         /*
4397          * Make sure we didn't race:
4398          */
4399         if (unlikely(hlock_class(this)->usage_mask & new_mask))
4400                 goto unlock;
4401 
4402         if (!hlock_class(this)->usage_mask)
4403                 debug_atomic_dec(nr_unused_locks);
4404 
4405         hlock_class(this)->usage_mask |= new_mask;
4406 
4407         if (new_bit < LOCK_TRACE_STATES) {
4408                 if (!(hlock_class(this)->usage_traces[new_bit] = save_trace()))
4409                         return 0;
4410         }
4411 
4412         if (new_bit < LOCK_USED) {
4413                 ret = mark_lock_irq(curr, this, new_bit);
4414                 if (!ret)
4415                         return 0;
4416         }
4417 
4418 unlock:
4419         graph_unlock();
4420 
4421         /*
4422          * We must printk outside of the graph_lock:
4423          */
4424         if (ret == 2) {
4425                 printk("\nmarked lock as {%s}:\n", usage_str[new_bit]);
4426                 print_lock(this);
4427                 print_irqtrace_events(curr);
4428                 dump_stack();
4429         }
4430 
4431         return ret;
4432 }

4434 static inline short task_wait_context(struct task_struct *curr)
     /*   */
4435 {
4436         /*
4437          * Set appropriate wait type for the context; for IRQs we have to take
4438          * into account force_irqthread as that is implied by PREEMPT_RT.
4439          */
4440         if (lockdep_hardirq_context()) {
4441                 /*
4442                  * Check if force_irqthreads will run us threaded.
4443                  */
4444                 if (curr->hardirq_threaded || curr->irq_config)
4445                         return LD_WAIT_CONFIG;
4446 
4447                 return LD_WAIT_SPIN;
4448         } else if (curr->softirq_context) {
4449                 /*
4450                  * Softirqs are always threaded.
4451                  */
4452                 return LD_WAIT_CONFIG;
4453         }
4454 
4455         return LD_WAIT_MAX;
4456 }

4491 /*
4492  * Verify the wait_type context.
4493  *
4494  * This check validates we takes locks in the right wait-type order; that is it
4495  * ensures that we do not take mutexes inside spinlocks and do not attempt to
4496  * acquire spinlocks inside raw_spinlocks and the sort.
4497  *
4498  * The entire thing is slightly more complex because of RCU, RCU is a lock that
4499  * can be taken from (pretty much) any context but also has constraints.
4500  * However when taken in a stricter environment the RCU lock does not loosen
4501  * the constraints.
4502  *
4503  * Therefore we must look for the strictest environment in the lock stack and
4504  * compare that to the lock we're trying to acquire.
4505  */
4506 static int check_wait_context(struct task_struct *curr, struct held_lock *next)
     /*   */
4507 {
4508         short next_inner = hlock_class(next)->wait_type_inner;
4509         short next_outer = hlock_class(next)->wait_type_outer;
4510         short curr_inner;
4511         int depth;
4512 
4513         if (!curr->lockdep_depth || !next_inner || next->trylock)
4514                 return 0;
4515 
4516         if (!next_outer)
4517                 next_outer = next_inner;
4518 
4519         /*
4520          * Find start of current irq_context..
4521          */
4522         for (depth = curr->lockdep_depth - 1; depth >= 0; depth--) {
4523                 struct held_lock *prev = curr->held_locks + depth;
4524                 if (prev->irq_context != next->irq_context)
4525                         break;
4526         }
4527         depth++;
4528 
4529         curr_inner = task_wait_context(curr);
4530 
4531         for (; depth < curr->lockdep_depth; depth++) {
4532                 struct held_lock *prev = curr->held_locks + depth;
4533                 short prev_inner = hlock_class(prev)->wait_type_inner;
4534 
4535                 if (prev_inner) {
4536                         /*
4537                          * We can have a bigger inner than a previous one
4538                          * when outer is smaller than inner, as with RCU.
4539                          *
4540                          * Also due to trylocks.
4541                          */
4542                         curr_inner = min(curr_inner, prev_inner);
4543                 }
4544         }
4545 
4546         if (next_outer > curr_inner)
4547                 return print_lock_invalid_wait_context(curr, next);
4548 
4549         return 0;
4550 }

4579 /*
4580  * Initialize a lock instance's lock-class mapping info:
4581  */
4582 void lockdep_init_map_waits(struct lockdep_map *lock, const char *name,
     /*   */
4583                             struct lock_class_key *key, int subclass,
4584                             short inner, short outer)
4585 {
4586         int i;
4587 
4588         for (i = 0; i < NR_LOCKDEP_CACHING_CLASSES; i++)
4589                 lock->class_cache[i] = NULL;
4590 
4591 #ifdef CONFIG_LOCK_STAT
4592         lock->cpu = raw_smp_processor_id();
4593 #endif
4594 
4595         /*
4596          * Can't be having no nameless bastards around this place!
4597          */
4598         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!name)) {
4599                 lock->name = "NULL";
4600                 return;
4601         }
4602 
4603         lock->name = name;
4604 
4605         lock->wait_type_outer = outer;
4606         lock->wait_type_inner = inner;
4607 
4608         /*
4609          * No key, no joy, we need to hash something.
4610          */
4611         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!key))
4612                 return;
4613         /*
4614          * Sanity check, the lock-class key must either have been allocated
4615          * statically or must have been registered as a dynamic key.
4616          */
4617         if (!static_obj(key) && !is_dynamic_key(key)) {
4618                 if (debug_locks)
4619                         printk(KERN_ERR "BUG: key %px has not been registered!\n", key);
4620                 DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(1);
4621                 return;
4622         }
4623         lock->key = key;
4624 
4625         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
4626                 return;
4627 
4628         if (subclass) {
4629                 unsigned long flags;
4630 
4631                 if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!lockdep_enabled()))
4632                         return;
4633 
4634                 raw_local_irq_save(flags);
4635                 lockdep_recursion_inc();
4636                 register_lock_class(lock, subclass, 1);
4637                 lockdep_recursion_finish();
4638                 raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
4639         }
4640 }
4641 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(lockdep_init_map_waits);
