4677 
4678 static int __lock_is_held(const struct lockdep_map *lock, int read);
4679 
4680 /*
4681  * This gets called for every mutex_lock*()/spin_lock*() operation.
4682  * We maintain the dependency maps and validate the locking attempt:
4683  *
4684  * The callers must make sure that IRQs are disabled before calling it,
4685  * otherwise we could get an interrupt which would want to take locks,
4686  * which would end up in lockdep again.
4687  */
4688 static int __lock_acquire(struct lockdep_map *lock, unsigned int subclass,
     /*   */
4689                           int trylock, int read, int check, int hardirqs_off,
4690                           struct lockdep_map *nest_lock, unsigned long ip,
4691                           int references, int pin_count)
4692 {
4693         struct task_struct *curr = current;
4694         struct lock_class *class = NULL;
4695         struct held_lock *hlock;
4696         unsigned int depth;
4697         int chain_head = 0;
4698         int class_idx;
4699         u64 chain_key;
4700 
4701         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
4702                 return 0;
4703 
4704         if (!prove_locking || lock->key == &__lockdep_no_validate__)
4705                 check = 0;
4706 
4707         if (subclass < NR_LOCKDEP_CACHING_CLASSES)
4708                 class = lock->class_cache[subclass];
4709         /*
4710          * Not cached?
4711          */
4712         if (unlikely(!class)) {
4713                 class = register_lock_class(lock, subclass, 0);
4714                 if (!class)
4715                         return 0;
4716         }
4717 
4718         debug_class_ops_inc(class);
4719 
4720         if (very_verbose(class)) {
4721                 printk("\nacquire class [%px] %s", class->key, class->name);
4722                 if (class->name_version > 1)
4723                         printk(KERN_CONT "#%d", class->name_version);
4724                 printk(KERN_CONT "\n");
4725                 dump_stack();
4726         }
4727 
4728         /*
4729          * Add the lock to the list of currently held locks.
4730          * (we dont increase the depth just yet, up until the
4731          * dependency checks are done)
4732          */
4733         depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
4734         /*
4735          * Ran out of static storage for our per-task lock stack again have we?
4736          */
4737         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(depth >= MAX_LOCK_DEPTH))
4738                 return 0;
4739 
4740         class_idx = class - lock_classes;
4741 
4742         if (depth) { /* we're holding locks */
4743                 hlock = curr->held_locks + depth - 1;
4744                 if (hlock->class_idx == class_idx && nest_lock) {
4745                         if (!references)
4746                                 references++;
4747 
4748                         if (!hlock->references)
4749                                 hlock->references++;
4750 
4751                         hlock->references += references;
4752 
4753                         /* Overflow */
4754                         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(hlock->references < references))
4755                                 return 0;
4756 
4757                         return 2;
4758                 }
4759         }
4760 
4761         hlock = curr->held_locks + depth;
4762         /*
4763          * Plain impossible, we just registered it and checked it weren't no
4764          * NULL like.. I bet this mushroom I ate was good!
4765          */
4766         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!class))
4767                 return 0;
4768         hlock->class_idx = class_idx;
4769         hlock->acquire_ip = ip;
4770         hlock->instance = lock;
4771         hlock->nest_lock = nest_lock;
4772         hlock->irq_context = task_irq_context(curr);
4773         hlock->trylock = trylock;
4774         hlock->read = read;
4775         hlock->check = check;
4776         hlock->hardirqs_off = !!hardirqs_off;
4777         hlock->references = references;
4778 #ifdef CONFIG_LOCK_STAT
4779         hlock->waittime_stamp = 0;
4780         hlock->holdtime_stamp = lockstat_clock();
4781 #endif
4782         hlock->pin_count = pin_count;
4783 
4784         if (check_wait_context(curr, hlock))
4785                 return 0;
4786 
4787         /* Initialize the lock usage bit */
4788         if (!mark_usage(curr, hlock, check))
4789                 return 0;
4790 
4791         /*
4792          * Calculate the chain hash: it's the combined hash of all the
4793          * lock keys along the dependency chain. We save the hash value
4794          * at every step so that we can get the current hash easily
4795          * after unlock. The chain hash is then used to cache dependency
4796          * results.
4797          *
4798          * The 'key ID' is what is the most compact key value to drive
4799          * the hash, not class->key.
4800          */
4801         /*
4802          * Whoops, we did it again.. class_idx is invalid.
4803          */
4804         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!test_bit(class_idx, lock_classes_in_use)))
4805                 return 0;
4806 
4807         chain_key = curr->curr_chain_key;
4808         if (!depth) {
4809                 /*
4810                  * How can we have a chain hash when we ain't got no keys?!
4811                  */
4812                 if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(chain_key != INITIAL_CHAIN_KEY))
4813                         return 0;
4814                 chain_head = 1;
4815         }
4816 
4817         hlock->prev_chain_key = chain_key;
4818         if (separate_irq_context(curr, hlock)) {
4819                 chain_key = INITIAL_CHAIN_KEY;
4820                 chain_head = 1;
4821         }
4822         chain_key = iterate_chain_key(chain_key, hlock_id(hlock));
4823 
4824         if (nest_lock && !__lock_is_held(nest_lock, -1)) {
4825                 print_lock_nested_lock_not_held(curr, hlock, ip);
4826                 return 0;
4827         }
4828 
4829         if (!debug_locks_silent) {
4830                 WARN_ON_ONCE(depth && !hlock_class(hlock - 1)->key);
4831                 WARN_ON_ONCE(!hlock_class(hlock)->key);
4832         }
4833 
4834         if (!validate_chain(curr, hlock, chain_head, chain_key))
4835                 return 0;
4836 
4837         curr->curr_chain_key = chain_key;
4838         curr->lockdep_depth++;
4839         check_chain_key(curr);
4840 #ifdef CONFIG_DEBUG_LOCKDEP
4841         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
4842                 return 0;
4843 #endif
4844         if (unlikely(curr->lockdep_depth >= MAX_LOCK_DEPTH)) {
4845                 debug_locks_off();
4846                 print_lockdep_off("BUG: MAX_LOCK_DEPTH too low!");
4847                 printk(KERN_DEBUG "depth: %i  max: %lu!\n",
4848                        curr->lockdep_depth, MAX_LOCK_DEPTH);
4849 
4850                 lockdep_print_held_locks(current);
4851                 debug_show_all_locks();
4852                 dump_stack();
4853 
4854                 return 0;
4855         }
4856 
4857         if (unlikely(curr->lockdep_depth > max_lockdep_depth))
4858                 max_lockdep_depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
4859 
4860         return 1;
4861 }

4890 static noinstr int match_held_lock(const struct held_lock *hlock,
     /*   */
4891                                    const struct lockdep_map *lock)
4892 {
4893         if (hlock->instance == lock)
4894                 return 1;
4895 
4896         if (hlock->references) {
4897                 const struct lock_class *class = lock->class_cache[0];
4898 
4899                 if (!class)
4900                         class = look_up_lock_class(lock, 0);
4901 
4902                 /*
4903                  * If look_up_lock_class() failed to find a class, we're trying
4904                  * to test if we hold a lock that has never yet been acquired.
4905                  * Clearly if the lock hasn't been acquired _ever_, we're not
4906                  * holding it either, so report failure.
4907                  */
4908                 if (!class)
4909                         return 0;
4910 
4911                 /*
4912                  * References, but not a lock we're actually ref-counting?
4913                  * State got messed up, follow the sites that change ->references
4914                  * and try to make sense of it.
4915                  */
4916                 if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!hlock->nest_lock))
4917                         return 0;
4918 
4919                 if (hlock->class_idx == class - lock_classes)
4920                         return 1;
4921         }
4922 
4923         return 0;
4924 }
4925 
4926 /* @depth must not be zero */
4927 static struct held_lock *find_held_lock(struct task_struct *curr,
     /*   */
4928                                         struct lockdep_map *lock,
4929                                         unsigned int depth, int *idx)
4930 {
4931         struct held_lock *ret, *hlock, *prev_hlock;
4932         int i;
4933 
4934         i = depth - 1;
4935         hlock = curr->held_locks + i;
4936         ret = hlock;
4937         if (match_held_lock(hlock, lock))
4938                 goto out;
4939 
4940         ret = NULL;
4941         for (i--, prev_hlock = hlock--;
4942              i >= 0;
4943              i--, prev_hlock = hlock--) {
4944                 /*
4945                  * We must not cross into another context:
4946                  */
4947                 if (prev_hlock->irq_context != hlock->irq_context) {
4948                         ret = NULL;
4949                         break;
4950                 }
4951                 if (match_held_lock(hlock, lock)) {
4952                         ret = hlock;
4953                         break;
4954                 }
4955         }
4956 
4957 out:
4958         *idx = i;
4959         return ret;
4960 }
4961 
4962 static int reacquire_held_locks(struct task_struct *curr, unsigned int depth,
     /*   */
4963                                 int idx, unsigned int *merged)
4964 {
4965         struct held_lock *hlock;
4966         int first_idx = idx;
4967 
4968         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!irqs_disabled()))
4969                 return 0;
4970 
4971         for (hlock = curr->held_locks + idx; idx < depth; idx++, hlock++) {
4972                 switch (__lock_acquire(hlock->instance,
4973                                     hlock_class(hlock)->subclass,
4974                                     hlock->trylock,
4975                                     hlock->read, hlock->check,
4976                                     hlock->hardirqs_off,
4977                                     hlock->nest_lock, hlock->acquire_ip,
4978                                     hlock->references, hlock->pin_count)) {
4979                 case 0:
4980                         return 1;
4981                 case 1:
4982                         break;
4983                 case 2:
4984                         *merged += (idx == first_idx);
4985                         break;
4986                 default:
4987                         WARN_ON(1);
4988                         return 0;
4989                 }
4990         }
4991         return 0;
4992 }

4994 static int
4995 __lock_set_class(struct lockdep_map *lock, const char *name,
     /*   */
4996                  struct lock_class_key *key, unsigned int subclass,
4997                  unsigned long ip)
4998 {
4999         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5000         unsigned int depth, merged = 0;
5001         struct held_lock *hlock;
5002         struct lock_class *class;
5003         int i;
5004 
5005         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
5006                 return 0;
5007 
5008         depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
5009         /*
5010          * This function is about (re)setting the class of a held lock,
5011          * yet we're not actually holding any locks. Naughty user!
5012          */
5013         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!depth))
5014                 return 0;
5015 
5016         hlock = find_held_lock(curr, lock, depth, &i);
5017         if (!hlock) {
5018                 print_unlock_imbalance_bug(curr, lock, ip);
5019                 return 0;
5020         }
5021 
5022         lockdep_init_map_waits(lock, name, key, 0,
5023                                lock->wait_type_inner,
5024                                lock->wait_type_outer);
5025         class = register_lock_class(lock, subclass, 0);
5026         hlock->class_idx = class - lock_classes;
5027 
5028         curr->lockdep_depth = i;
5029         curr->curr_chain_key = hlock->prev_chain_key;
5030 
5031         if (reacquire_held_locks(curr, depth, i, &merged))
5032                 return 0;
5033 
5034         /*
5035          * I took it apart and put it back together again, except now I have
5036          * these 'spare' parts.. where shall I put them.
5037          */
5038         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(curr->lockdep_depth != depth - merged))
5039                 return 0;
5040         return 1;
5041 }
5042 
5043 static int __lock_downgrade(struct lockdep_map *lock, unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
5044 {
5045         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5046         unsigned int depth, merged = 0;
5047         struct held_lock *hlock;
5048         int i;
5049 
5050         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
5051                 return 0;
5052 
5053         depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
5054         /*
5055          * This function is about (re)setting the class of a held lock,
5056          * yet we're not actually holding any locks. Naughty user!
5057          */
5058         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!depth))
5059                 return 0;
5060 
5061         hlock = find_held_lock(curr, lock, depth, &i);
5062         if (!hlock) {
5063                 print_unlock_imbalance_bug(curr, lock, ip);
5064                 return 0;
5065         }
5066 
5067         curr->lockdep_depth = i;
5068         curr->curr_chain_key = hlock->prev_chain_key;
5069 
5070         WARN(hlock->read, "downgrading a read lock");
5071         hlock->read = 1;
5072         hlock->acquire_ip = ip;
5073 
5074         if (reacquire_held_locks(curr, depth, i, &merged))
5075                 return 0;
5076 
5077         /* Merging can't happen with unchanged classes.. */
5078         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(merged))
5079                 return 0;
5080 
5081         /*
5082          * I took it apart and put it back together again, except now I have
5083          * these 'spare' parts.. where shall I put them.
5084          */
5085         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(curr->lockdep_depth != depth))
5086                 return 0;
5087 
5088         return 1;
5089 }
5090 
5091 /*
5092  * Remove the lock from the list of currently held locks - this gets
5093  * called on mutex_unlock()/spin_unlock*() (or on a failed
5094  * mutex_lock_interruptible()).
5095  */
5096 static int
5097 __lock_release(struct lockdep_map *lock, unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
5098 {
5099         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5100         unsigned int depth, merged = 1;
5101         struct held_lock *hlock;
5102         int i;
5103 
5104         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
5105                 return 0;
5106 
5107         depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
5108         /*
5109          * So we're all set to release this lock.. wait what lock? We don't
5110          * own any locks, you've been drinking again?
5111          */
5112         if (depth <= 0) {
5113                 print_unlock_imbalance_bug(curr, lock, ip);
5114                 return 0;
5115         }
5116 
5117         /*
5118          * Check whether the lock exists in the current stack
5119          * of held locks:
5120          */
5121         hlock = find_held_lock(curr, lock, depth, &i);
5122         if (!hlock) {
5123                 print_unlock_imbalance_bug(curr, lock, ip);
5124                 return 0;
5125         }
5126 
5127         if (hlock->instance == lock)
5128                 lock_release_holdtime(hlock);
5129 
5130         WARN(hlock->pin_count, "releasing a pinned lock\n");
5131 
5132         if (hlock->references) {
5133                 hlock->references--;
5134                 if (hlock->references) {
5135                         /*
5136                          * We had, and after removing one, still have
5137                          * references, the current lock stack is still
5138                          * valid. We're done!
5139                          */
5140                         return 1;
5141                 }
5142         }
5143 
5144         /*
5145          * We have the right lock to unlock, 'hlock' points to it.
5146          * Now we remove it from the stack, and add back the other
5147          * entries (if any), recalculating the hash along the way:
5148          */
5149 
5150         curr->lockdep_depth = i;
5151         curr->curr_chain_key = hlock->prev_chain_key;
5152 
5153         /*
5154          * The most likely case is when the unlock is on the innermost
5155          * lock. In this case, we are done!
5156          */
5157         if (i == depth-1)
5158                 return 1;
5159 
5160         if (reacquire_held_locks(curr, depth, i + 1, &merged))
5161                 return 0;
5162 
5163         /*
5164          * We had N bottles of beer on the wall, we drank one, but now
5165          * there's not N-1 bottles of beer left on the wall...
5166          * Pouring two of the bottles together is acceptable.
5167          */
5168         DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(curr->lockdep_depth != depth - merged);
5169 
5170         /*
5171          * Since reacquire_held_locks() would have called check_chain_key()
5172          * indirectly via __lock_acquire(), we don't need to do it again
5173          * on return.
5174          */
5175         return 0;
5176 }
5177 
5178 static __always_inline
5179 int __lock_is_held(const struct lockdep_map *lock, int read)
     /*   */
5180 {
5181         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5182         int i;
5183 
5184         for (i = 0; i < curr->lockdep_depth; i++) {
5185                 struct held_lock *hlock = curr->held_locks + i;
5186 
5187                 if (match_held_lock(hlock, lock)) {
5188                         if (read == -1 || hlock->read == read)
5189                                 return 1;
5190 
5191                         return 0;
5192                 }
5193         }
5194 
5195         return 0;
5196 }
5197 
5198 static struct pin_cookie __lock_pin_lock(struct lockdep_map *lock)
     /*   */
5199 {
5200         struct pin_cookie cookie = NIL_COOKIE;
5201         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5202         int i;
5203 
5204         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
5205                 return cookie;
5206 
5207         for (i = 0; i < curr->lockdep_depth; i++) {
5208                 struct held_lock *hlock = curr->held_locks + i;
5209 
5210                 if (match_held_lock(hlock, lock)) {
5211                         /*
5212                          * Grab 16bits of randomness; this is sufficient to not
5213                          * be guessable and still allows some pin nesting in
5214                          * our u32 pin_count.
5215                          */
5216                         cookie.val = 1 + (prandom_u32() >> 16);
5217                         hlock->pin_count += cookie.val;
5218                         return cookie;
5219                 }
5220         }
5221 
5222         WARN(1, "pinning an unheld lock\n");
5223         return cookie;
5224 }

5226 static void __lock_repin_lock(struct lockdep_map *lock, struct pin_cookie cookie)
     /*   */
5227 {
5228         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5229         int i;
5230 
5231         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
5232                 return;
5233 
5234         for (i = 0; i < curr->lockdep_depth; i++) {
5235                 struct held_lock *hlock = curr->held_locks + i;
5236 
5237                 if (match_held_lock(hlock, lock)) {
5238                         hlock->pin_count += cookie.val;
5239                         return;
5240                 }
5241         }
5242 
5243         WARN(1, "pinning an unheld lock\n");
5244 }
5245 
5246 static void __lock_unpin_lock(struct lockdep_map *lock, struct pin_cookie cookie)
     /*   */
5247 {
5248         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5249         int i;
5250 
5251         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
5252                 return;
5253 
5254         for (i = 0; i < curr->lockdep_depth; i++) {
5255                 struct held_lock *hlock = curr->held_locks + i;
5256 
5257                 if (match_held_lock(hlock, lock)) {
5258                         if (WARN(!hlock->pin_count, "unpinning an unpinned lock\n"))
5259                                 return;
5260 
5261                         hlock->pin_count -= cookie.val;
5262 
5263                         if (WARN((int)hlock->pin_count < 0, "pin count corrupted\n"))
5264                                 hlock->pin_count = 0;
5265 
5266                         return;
5267                 }
5268         }
5269 
5270         WARN(1, "unpinning an unheld lock\n");
5271 }

5273 /*
5274  * Check whether we follow the irq-flags state precisely:
5275  */
5276 static noinstr void check_flags(unsigned long flags)
     /*   */
5277 {
5278 #if defined(CONFIG_PROVE_LOCKING) && defined(CONFIG_DEBUG_LOCKDEP)
5279         if (!debug_locks)
5280                 return;
5281 
5282         /* Get the warning out..  */
5283         instrumentation_begin();
5284 
5285         if (irqs_disabled_flags(flags)) {
5286                 if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(lockdep_hardirqs_enabled())) {
5287                         printk("possible reason: unannotated irqs-off.\n");
5288                 }
5289         } else {
5290                 if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!lockdep_hardirqs_enabled())) {
5291                         printk("possible reason: unannotated irqs-on.\n");
5292                 }
5293         }
5294 
5295         /*
5296          * We dont accurately track softirq state in e.g.
5297          * hardirq contexts (such as on 4KSTACKS), so only
5298          * check if not in hardirq contexts:
5299          */
5300         if (!hardirq_count()) {
5301                 if (softirq_count()) {
5302                         /* like the above, but with softirqs */
5303                         DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(current->softirqs_enabled);
5304                 } else {
5305                         /* lick the above, does it taste good? */
5306                         DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!current->softirqs_enabled);
5307                 }
5308         }
5309 
5310         if (!debug_locks)
5311                 print_irqtrace_events(current);
5312 
5313         instrumentation_end();
5314 #endif
5315 }

5353 /* NMI context !!! */
5354 static void verify_lock_unused(struct lockdep_map *lock, struct held_lock *hlock, int subclass)
     /*   */
5355 {
5356 #ifdef CONFIG_PROVE_LOCKING
5357         struct lock_class *class = look_up_lock_class(lock, subclass);
5358         unsigned long mask = LOCKF_USED;
5359 
5360         /* if it doesn't have a class (yet), it certainly hasn't been used yet */
5361         if (!class)
5362                 return;
5363 
5364         /*
5365          * READ locks only conflict with USED, such that if we only ever use
5366          * READ locks, there is no deadlock possible -- RCU.
5367          */
5368         if (!hlock->read)
5369                 mask |= LOCKF_USED_READ;
5370 
5371         if (!(class->usage_mask & mask))
5372                 return;
5373 
5374         hlock->class_idx = class - lock_classes;
5375 
5376         print_usage_bug(current, hlock, LOCK_USED, LOCK_USAGE_STATES);
5377 #endif
5378 }

5405 /*
5406  * We are not always called with irqs disabled - do that here,
5407  * and also avoid lockdep recursion:
5408  */
5409 void lock_acquire(struct lockdep_map *lock, unsigned int subclass,
     /*   */
5410                           int trylock, int read, int check,
5411                           struct lockdep_map *nest_lock, unsigned long ip)
5412 {
5413         unsigned long flags;
5414 
5415         trace_lock_acquire(lock, subclass, trylock, read, check, nest_lock, ip);
5416 
5417         if (!debug_locks)
5418                 return;
5419 
5420         if (unlikely(!lockdep_enabled())) {
5421                 /* XXX allow trylock from NMI ?!? */
5422                 if (lockdep_nmi() && !trylock) {
5423                         struct held_lock hlock;
5424 
5425                         hlock.acquire_ip = ip;
5426                         hlock.instance = lock;
5427                         hlock.nest_lock = nest_lock;

5431                         hlock.check = check;

5442

5445                        irqs_disabled_flags(flags), nest_lock, ip, 0, 0);
5446         lockdep_recursion_finish();
5447         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
5448 }

5574 static void
5575 __lock_contended(struct lockdep_map *lock, unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
5576 {
5577         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5578         struct held_lock *hlock;
5579         struct lock_class_stats *stats;
5580         unsigned int depth;
5581         int i, contention_point, contending_point;
5582 
5583         depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
5584         /*
5585          * Whee, we contended on this lock, except it seems we're not
5586          * actually trying to acquire anything much at all..
5587          */
5588         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!depth))
5589                 return;
5590 
5591         hlock = find_held_lock(curr, lock, depth, &i);
5592         if (!hlock) {
5593                 print_lock_contention_bug(curr, lock, ip);
5594                 return;
5595         }
5596 
5597         if (hlock->instance != lock)
5598                 return;
5599 
5600         hlock->waittime_stamp = lockstat_clock();
5601 
5602         contention_point = lock_point(hlock_class(hlock)->contention_point, ip);
5603         contending_point = lock_point(hlock_class(hlock)->contending_point,
5604                                       lock->ip);
5605 
5606         stats = get_lock_stats(hlock_class(hlock));
5607         if (contention_point < LOCKSTAT_POINTS)
5608                 stats->contention_point[contention_point]++;
5609         if (contending_point < LOCKSTAT_POINTS)
5610                 stats->contending_point[contending_point]++;
5611         if (lock->cpu != smp_processor_id())
5612                 stats->bounces[bounce_contended + !!hlock->read]++;
5613 }
5614 
5615 static void
5616 __lock_acquired(struct lockdep_map *lock, unsigned long ip)
     /*   */
5617 {
5618         struct task_struct *curr = current;
5619         struct held_lock *hlock;
5620         struct lock_class_stats *stats;
5621         unsigned int depth;
5622         u64 now, waittime = 0;
5623         int i, cpu;
5624 
5625         depth = curr->lockdep_depth;
5626         /*
5627          * Yay, we acquired ownership of this lock we didn't try to
5628          * acquire, how the heck did that happen?
5629          */
5630         if (DEBUG_LOCKS_WARN_ON(!depth))
5631                 return;
5632 
5633         hlock = find_held_lock(curr, lock, depth, &i);
5634         if (!hlock) {
5635                 print_lock_contention_bug(curr, lock, _RET_IP_);
5636                 return;
5637         }
5638 
5639         if (hlock->instance != lock)
5640                 return;
5641 
5642         cpu = smp_processor_id();
5643         if (hlock->waittime_stamp) {
5644                 now = lockstat_clock();
5645                 waittime = now - hlock->waittime_stamp;
5646                 hlock->holdtime_stamp = now;
5647         }
5648 
5649         stats = get_lock_stats(hlock_class(hlock));
5650         if (waittime) {
5651                 if (hlock->read)
5652                         lock_time_inc(&stats->read_waittime, waittime);
5653                 else
5654                         lock_time_inc(&stats->write_waittime, waittime);
5655         }
5656         if (lock->cpu != cpu)
5657                 stats->bounces[bounce_acquired + !!hlock->read]++;
5658 
5659         lock->cpu = cpu;
5660         lock->ip = ip;
5661 }

5700 /*
5701  * Used by the testsuite, sanitize the validator state
5702  * after a simulated failure:
5703  */
5704 
5705 void lockdep_reset(void)
     /*   */
5706 {
5707         unsigned long flags;
5708         int i;
5709 
5710         raw_local_irq_save(flags);
5711         lockdep_init_task(current);
5712         memset(current->held_locks, 0, MAX_LOCK_DEPTH*sizeof(struct held_lock));
5713         nr_hardirq_chains = 0;
5714         nr_softirq_chains = 0;
5715         nr_process_chains = 0;
5716         debug_locks = 1;
5717         for (i = 0; i < CHAINHASH_SIZE; i++)
5718                 INIT_HLIST_HEAD(chainhash_table + i);
5719         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
5720 }
5721 
5722 /* Remove a class from a lock chain. Must be called with the graph lock held. */
5723 static void remove_class_from_lock_chain(struct pending_free *pf,
     /*   */
5724                                          struct lock_chain *chain,
5725                                          struct lock_class *class)
5726 {
5727 #ifdef CONFIG_PROVE_LOCKING
5728         int i;
5729 
5730         for (i = chain->base; i < chain->base + chain->depth; i++) {
5731                 if (chain_hlock_class_idx(chain_hlocks[i]) != class - lock_classes)
5732                         continue;
5733                 /*
5734                  * Each lock class occurs at most once in a lock chain so once
5735                  * we found a match we can break out of this loop.
5736                  */
5737                 goto free_lock_chain;
5738         }
5739         /* Since the chain has not been modified, return. */
5740         return;
5741 
5742 free_lock_chain:
5743         free_chain_hlocks(chain->base, chain->depth);
5744         /* Overwrite the chain key for concurrent RCU readers. */
5745         WRITE_ONCE(chain->chain_key, INITIAL_CHAIN_KEY);
5746         dec_chains(chain->irq_context);
5747 
5748         /*
5749          * Note: calling hlist_del_rcu() from inside a
5750          * hlist_for_each_entry_rcu() loop is safe.
5751          */
5752         hlist_del_rcu(&chain->entry);
5753         __set_bit(chain - lock_chains, pf->lock_chains_being_freed);
5754         nr_zapped_lock_chains++;
5755 #endif
5756 }
5757 
5758 /* Must be called with the graph lock held. */
5759 static void remove_class_from_lock_chains(struct pending_free *pf,
     /*   */
5760                                           struct lock_class *class)
5761 {
5762         struct lock_chain *chain;
5763         struct hlist_head *head;
5764         int i;
5765 
5766         for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(chainhash_table); i++) {
5767                 head = chainhash_table + i;
5768                 hlist_for_each_entry_rcu(chain, head, entry) {
5769                         remove_class_from_lock_chain(pf, chain, class);
5770                 }
5771         }
5772 }
5773 
5774 /*
5775  * Remove all references to a lock class. The caller must hold the graph lock.
5776  */
5777 static void zap_class(struct pending_free *pf, struct lock_class *class)
     /*   */
5778 {
5779         struct lock_list *entry;
5780         int i;
5781 
5782         WARN_ON_ONCE(!class->key);
5783 
5784         /*
5785          * Remove all dependencies this lock is
5786          * involved in:
5787          */
5788         for_each_set_bit(i, list_entries_in_use, ARRAY_SIZE(list_entries)) {
5789                 entry = list_entries + i;
5790                 if (entry->class != class && entry->links_to != class)
5791                         continue;
5792                 __clear_bit(i, list_entries_in_use);
5793                 nr_list_entries--;
5794                 list_del_rcu(&entry->entry);
5795         }
5796         if (list_empty(&class->locks_after) &&
5797             list_empty(&class->locks_before)) {
5798                 list_move_tail(&class->lock_entry, &pf->zapped);
5799                 hlist_del_rcu(&class->hash_entry);
5800                 WRITE_ONCE(class->key, NULL);
5801                 WRITE_ONCE(class->name, NULL);
5802                 nr_lock_classes--;
5803                 __clear_bit(class - lock_classes, lock_classes_in_use);
5804         } else {
5805                 WARN_ONCE(true, "%s() failed for class %s\n", __func__,
5806                           class->name);
5807         }
5808 
5809         remove_class_from_lock_chains(pf, class);
5810         nr_zapped_classes++;
5811 }
5812 
5813 static void reinit_class(struct lock_class *class)
     /*   */
5814 {
5815         void *const p = class;
5816         const unsigned int offset = offsetof(struct lock_class, key);
5817 
5818         WARN_ON_ONCE(!class->lock_entry.next);
5819         WARN_ON_ONCE(!list_empty(&class->locks_after));
5820         WARN_ON_ONCE(!list_empty(&class->locks_before));
5821         memset(p + offset, 0, sizeof(*class) - offset);
5822         WARN_ON_ONCE(!class->lock_entry.next);
5823         WARN_ON_ONCE(!list_empty(&class->locks_after));
5824         WARN_ON_ONCE(!list_empty(&class->locks_before));
5825 }
5826 
5827 static inline int within(const void *addr, void *start, unsigned long size)
     /*   */
5828 {
5829         return addr >= start && addr < start + size;
5830 }
5831 
5832 static bool inside_selftest(void)
     /*   */
5833 {
5834         return current == lockdep_selftest_task_struct;
5835 }
5836 
5837 /* The caller must hold the graph lock. */
5838 static struct pending_free *get_pending_free(void)
     /*   */
5839 {
5840         return delayed_free.pf + delayed_free.index;
5841 }
5842 
5843 static void free_zapped_rcu(struct rcu_head *cb);
5844 
5845 /*
5846  * Schedule an RCU callback if no RCU callback is pending. Must be called with
5847  * the graph lock held.
5848  */
5849 static void call_rcu_zapped(struct pending_free *pf)
     /*   */
5850 {
5851         WARN_ON_ONCE(inside_selftest());
5852 
5853         if (list_empty(&pf->zapped))
5854                 return;
5855 
5856         if (delayed_free.scheduled)
5857                 return;
5858 
5859         delayed_free.scheduled = true;
5860 
5861         WARN_ON_ONCE(delayed_free.pf + delayed_free.index != pf);
5862         delayed_free.index ^= 1;
5863 
5864         call_rcu(&delayed_free.rcu_head, free_zapped_rcu);
5865 }
5866 
5867 /* The caller must hold the graph lock. May be called from RCU context. */
5868 static void __free_zapped_classes(struct pending_free *pf)
     /*   */
5869 {
5870         struct lock_class *class;
5871 
5872         check_data_structures();
5873 
5874         list_for_each_entry(class, &pf->zapped, lock_entry)
5875                 reinit_class(class);
5876 
5877         list_splice_init(&pf->zapped, &free_lock_classes);
5878 
5879 #ifdef CONFIG_PROVE_LOCKING
5880         bitmap_andnot(lock_chains_in_use, lock_chains_in_use,
5881                       pf->lock_chains_being_freed, ARRAY_SIZE(lock_chains));
5882         bitmap_clear(pf->lock_chains_being_freed, 0, ARRAY_SIZE(lock_chains));
5883 #endif
5884 }
5885 
5886 static void free_zapped_rcu(struct rcu_head *ch)
     /*   */
5887 {
5888         struct pending_free *pf;
5889         unsigned long flags;
5890 
5891         if (WARN_ON_ONCE(ch != &delayed_free.rcu_head))
5892                 return;
5893 
5894         raw_local_irq_save(flags);
5895         lockdep_lock();
5896 
5897         /* closed head */
5898         pf = delayed_free.pf + (delayed_free.index ^ 1);
5899         __free_zapped_classes(pf);
5900         delayed_free.scheduled = false;
5901 
5902         /*
5903          * If there's anything on the open list, close and start a new callback.
5904          */
5905         call_rcu_zapped(delayed_free.pf + delayed_free.index);
5906 
5907         lockdep_unlock();
5908         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
5909 }
5910 
5911 /*
5912  * Remove all lock classes from the class hash table and from the
5913  * all_lock_classes list whose key or name is in the address range [start,
5914  * start + size). Move these lock classes to the zapped_classes list. Must
5915  * be called with the graph lock held.
5916  */
5917 static void __lockdep_free_key_range(struct pending_free *pf, void *start,
     /*   */
5918                                      unsigned long size)
5919 {
5920         struct lock_class *class;
5921         struct hlist_head *head;
5922         int i;
5923 
5924         /* Unhash all classes that were created by a module. */
5925         for (i = 0; i < CLASSHASH_SIZE; i++) {
5926                 head = classhash_table + i;
5927                 hlist_for_each_entry_rcu(class, head, hash_entry) {
5928                         if (!within(class->key, start, size) &&
5929                             !within(class->name, start, size))
5930                                 continue;
5931                         zap_class(pf, class);
5932                 }
5933         }
5934 }
5935 
5936 /*
5937  * Used in module.c to remove lock classes from memory that is going to be
5938  * freed; and possibly re-used by other modules.
5939  *
5940  * We will have had one synchronize_rcu() before getting here, so we're
5941  * guaranteed nobody will look up these exact classes -- they're properly dead
5942  * but still allocated.
5943  */
5944 static void lockdep_free_key_range_reg(void *start, unsigned long size)
     /*   */
5945 {
5946         struct pending_free *pf;
5947         unsigned long flags;
5948 
5949         init_data_structures_once();
5950 
5951         raw_local_irq_save(flags);
5952         lockdep_lock();
5953         pf = get_pending_free();
5954         __lockdep_free_key_range(pf, start, size);
5955         call_rcu_zapped(pf);
5956         lockdep_unlock();
5957         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
5958 
5959         /*
5960          * Wait for any possible iterators from look_up_lock_class() to pass
5961          * before continuing to free the memory they refer to.
5962          */
5963         synchronize_rcu();
5964 }
5965 
5966 /*
5967  * Free all lockdep keys in the range [start, start+size). Does not sleep.
5968  * Ignores debug_locks. Must only be used by the lockdep selftests.
5969  */
5970 static void lockdep_free_key_range_imm(void *start, unsigned long size)
     /*   */
5971 {
5972         struct pending_free *pf = delayed_free.pf;
5973         unsigned long flags;
5974 
5975         init_data_structures_once();
5976 
5977         raw_local_irq_save(flags);
5978         lockdep_lock();
5979         __lockdep_free_key_range(pf, start, size);
5980         __free_zapped_classes(pf);
5981         lockdep_unlock();
5982         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
5983 }
5984 
5985 void lockdep_free_key_range(void *start, unsigned long size)
     /*   */
5986 {
5987         init_data_structures_once();
5988 
5989         if (inside_selftest())
5990                 lockdep_free_key_range_imm(start, size);
5991         else
5992                 lockdep_free_key_range_reg(start, size);
5993 }

5995 /*
5996  * Check whether any element of the @lock->class_cache[] array refers to a
5997  * registered lock class. The caller must hold either the graph lock or the
5998  * RCU read lock.
5999  */
6000 static bool lock_class_cache_is_registered(struct lockdep_map *lock)
     /*   */
6001 {
6002         struct lock_class *class;
6003         struct hlist_head *head;
6004         int i, j;
6005 
6006         for (i = 0; i < CLASSHASH_SIZE; i++) {
6007                 head = classhash_table + i;
6008                 hlist_for_each_entry_rcu(class, head, hash_entry) {
6009                         for (j = 0; j < NR_LOCKDEP_CACHING_CLASSES; j++)
6010                                 if (lock->class_cache[j] == class)
6011                                         return true;
6012                 }
6013         }
6014         return false;
6015 }
6016 
6017 /* The caller must hold the graph lock. Does not sleep. */
6018 static void __lockdep_reset_lock(struct pending_free *pf,
     /*   */
6019                                  struct lockdep_map *lock)
6020 {
6021         struct lock_class *class;
6022         int j;
6023 
6024         /*
6025          * Remove all classes this lock might have:
6026          */
6027         for (j = 0; j < MAX_LOCKDEP_SUBCLASSES; j++) {
6028                 /*
6029                  * If the class exists we look it up and zap it:
6030                  */
6031                 class = look_up_lock_class(lock, j);
6032                 if (class)
6033                         zap_class(pf, class);
6034         }
6035         /*
6036          * Debug check: in the end all mapped classes should
6037          * be gone.
6038          */
6039         if (WARN_ON_ONCE(lock_class_cache_is_registered(lock)))
6040                 debug_locks_off();
6041 }
6042 
6043 /*
6044  * Remove all information lockdep has about a lock if debug_locks == 1. Free
6045  * released data structures from RCU context.
6046  */
6047 static void lockdep_reset_lock_reg(struct lockdep_map *lock)
     /*   */
6048 {
6049         struct pending_free *pf;
6050         unsigned long flags;
6051         int locked;
6052 
6053         raw_local_irq_save(flags);
6054         locked = graph_lock();
6055         if (!locked)
6056                 goto out_irq;
6057 
6058         pf = get_pending_free();
6059         __lockdep_reset_lock(pf, lock);
6060         call_rcu_zapped(pf);
6061 
6062         graph_unlock();
6063 out_irq:
6064         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
6065 }
6066 
6067 /*
6068  * Reset a lock. Does not sleep. Ignores debug_locks. Must only be used by the
6069  * lockdep selftests.
6070  */
6071 static void lockdep_reset_lock_imm(struct lockdep_map *lock)
     /*   */
6072 {
6073         struct pending_free *pf = delayed_free.pf;
6074         unsigned long flags;
6075 
6076         raw_local_irq_save(flags);
6077         lockdep_lock();
6078         __lockdep_reset_lock(pf, lock);
6079         __free_zapped_classes(pf);
6080         lockdep_unlock();
6081         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
6082 }
6083 
6084 void lockdep_reset_lock(struct lockdep_map *lock)
     /*   */
6085 {
6086         init_data_structures_once();
6087 
6088         if (inside_selftest())
6089                 lockdep_reset_lock_imm(lock);
6090         else
6091                 lockdep_reset_lock_reg(lock);
6092 }

6094 /* Unregister a dynamically allocated key. */
6095 void lockdep_unregister_key(struct lock_class_key *key)
     /*   */
6096 {
6097         struct hlist_head *hash_head = keyhashentry(key);
6098         struct lock_class_key *k;
6099         struct pending_free *pf;
6100         unsigned long flags;
6101         bool found = false;
6102 
6103         might_sleep();
6104 
6105         if (WARN_ON_ONCE(static_obj(key)))
6106                 return;
6107 
6108         raw_local_irq_save(flags);
6109         if (!graph_lock())
6110                 goto out_irq;
6111 
6112         pf = get_pending_free();
6113         hlist_for_each_entry_rcu(k, hash_head, hash_entry) {
6114                 if (k == key) {
6115                         hlist_del_rcu(&k->hash_entry);
6116                         found = true;
6117                         break;
6118                 }
6119         }
6120         WARN_ON_ONCE(!found);
6121         __lockdep_free_key_range(pf, key, 1);
6122         call_rcu_zapped(pf);
6123         graph_unlock();
6124 out_irq:
6125         raw_local_irq_restore(flags);
6126 
6127         /* Wait until is_dynamic_key() has finished accessing k->hash_entry. */
6128         synchronize_rcu();
6129 }

6201 /*
6202  * Called when kernel memory is freed (or unmapped), or if a lock
6203  * is destroyed or reinitialized - this code checks whether there is
6204  * any held lock in the memory range of <from> to <to>:
6205  */
6206 void debug_check_no_locks_freed(const void *mem_from, unsigned long mem_len)
     /*   */
6207 {

6209         struct held_lock *hlock;
6210         unsigned long flags;

6212 
6213         if (unlikely(!debug_locks))
6214                 return;

6218                 hlock = curr->held_locks + i;

6221                                         sizeof(*hlock->instance)))

6225                 break;
6226         }

6320 
6321 void lockdep_rcu_suspicious(const char *file, const int line, const char *s)
     /*   */
6322 {
6323         struct task_struct *curr = current;
6324 
6325         /* Note: the following can be executed concurrently, so be careful. */
6326         pr_warn("\n");
6327         pr_warn("=============================\n");
6328         pr_warn("WARNING: suspicious RCU usage\n");
6329         print_kernel_ident();
6330         pr_warn("-----------------------------\n");
6331         pr_warn("%s:%d %s!\n", file, line, s);
6332         pr_warn("\nother info that might help us debug this:\n\n");
6333         pr_warn("\n%srcu_scheduler_active = %d, debug_locks = %d\n",
6334                !rcu_lockdep_current_cpu_online()
6335                         ? "RCU used illegally from offline CPU!\n"
6336                         : "",
6337                rcu_scheduler_active, debug_locks);
6338 
6339         /*
6340          * If a CPU is in the RCU-free window in idle (ie: in the section
6341          * between rcu_idle_enter() and rcu_idle_exit(), then RCU
6342          * considers that CPU to be in an "extended quiescent state",
6343          * which means that RCU will be completely ignoring that CPU.
6344          * Therefore, rcu_read_lock() and friends have absolutely no
6345          * effect on a CPU running in that state. In other words, even if
6346          * such an RCU-idle CPU has called rcu_read_lock(), RCU might well
6347          * delete data structures out from under it.  RCU really has no
6348          * choice here: we need to keep an RCU-free window in idle where
6349          * the CPU may possibly enter into low power mode. This way we can
6350          * notice an extended quiescent state to other CPUs that started a grace
6351          * period. Otherwise we would delay any grace period as long as we run
6352          * in the idle task.
6353          *
6354          * So complain bitterly if someone does call rcu_read_lock(),
6355          * rcu_read_lock_bh() and so on from extended quiescent states.
6356          */
6357         if (!rcu_is_watching())
6358                 pr_warn("RCU used illegally from extended quiescent state!\n");
6359 
6360         lockdep_print_held_locks(curr);
6361         pr_warn("\nstack backtrace:\n");
6362         dump_stack();
6363 }
6364 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(lockdep_rcu_suspicious);
